[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] In probability theory and statistics, a **covariance matrix** (also known as **auto-covariance matrix**, **dispersion matrix**, **variance matrix**, or **varianceÔÇôcovariance matrix**) is a square matrix giving the covariance between each pair of elements of a given random vector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Intuitively, the covariance matrix generalizes the notion of variance to multiple dimensions.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Any covariance matrix is symmetric and positive semi-definite and its main diagonal contains variances (i.e., the covariance of each element with itself).
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The covariance matrix of a random vector $\mathbf {X}$ is typically denoted by $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {X} \mathbf {X} }$ , $\Sigma$ or S .
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Throughout this article, boldfaced unsubscripted $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ are used to refer to random vectors, and Roman subscripted $X_{i}$ and $Y_{i}$ are used to refer to scalar random variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Both forms are quite standard, and there is no ambiguity between them.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The matrix $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {X} \mathbf {X} }$ is also often called the **variance-covariance matrix**, since the diagonal terms are in fact variances.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Each element on the principal diagonal of a correlation matrix is the correlation of a random variable with itself, which always equals 1.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Each off-diagonal element is between Ôłĺ1 and +1 inclusive.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The inverse of this matrix, $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {X} \mathbf {X} }^{-1}$ , if it exists, is the inverse covariance matrix, also known as the *precision matrix* (or *concentration matrix*).
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] This duality motivates a number of other dualities between marginalizing and conditioning for Gaussian random variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {XX} }$ and $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {YY} }$ can be identified as the variance matrices of the marginal distributions for $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ respectively.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The matrix $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {YX} }\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {XX} }^{-1}$ is known as the matrix of regression coefficients, while in linear algebra $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {Y|X} }$ is the Schur complement of $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {XX} }$ in ${\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] In this form they correspond to the coefficients obtained by inverting the matrix of the normal equations of ordinary least squares (OLS).
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] A covariance matrix with all non-zero elements tells us that all the individual random variables are interrelated.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] This means that the variables are not only directly correlated, but also correlated via other variables indirectly.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Often such indirect, common-mode correlations are trivial and uninteresting.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] They can be suppressed by calculating the partial covariance matrix, that is the part of covariance matrix that shows only the interesting part of correlations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The standard deviation matrix $\mathbf {S}$ is the extension of the standard deviation to multiple dimensions.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] It is the symmetric square root of the covariance matrix $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Applied to one vector, the covariance matrix maps a linear combination **c** of the random variables **X** onto a vector of covariances with those variables: $\mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}\Sigma =\operatorname {cov} (\mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {X} )$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Treated as a bilinear form, it yields the covariance between the two linear combinations: $\mathbf {d} ^{\mathsf {T}}{\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}\mathbf {c} =\operatorname {cov} (\mathbf {d} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {X} )$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The variance of a linear combination is then $\mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}{\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}\mathbf {c}$ , its covariance with itself.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Similarly, the (pseudo-)inverse covariance matrix provides an inner product $\langle c-\mu |\Sigma ^{+}|c-\mu \rangle$ , which induces the Mahalanobis distance, a measure of the "unlikelihood" of *c*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Conversely, every symmetric positive semi-definite matrix is a covariance matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] To see this, suppose M is a $p\times p$ symmetric positive-semidefinite matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] From the finite-dimensional case of the spectral theorem, it follows that M has a nonnegative symmetric square root, which can be denoted by **M**1/2.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Let $\mathbf {X}$ be any $p\times 1$ column vector-valued random variable whose covariance matrix is the $p\times p$ identity matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] If $\mathbf {Z} =(Z_{1},\ldots ,Z_{n})^{\mathsf {T}}$ is a column vector of complex-valued random variables, then the conjugate transpose $\mathbf {Z} ^{\mathsf {H}}$ is formed by *both* transposing and conjugating.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] In contrast to the covariance matrix defined above, Hermitian transposition gets replaced by transposition in the definition.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Its diagonal elements may be complex valued; it is a complex symmetric matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] These empirical sample covariance matrices are the most straightforward and most often used estimators for the covariance matrices, but other estimators also exist, including regularised or shrinkage estimators, which may have better properties.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The covariance matrix is a useful tool in many different areas.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] This is called principal component analysis (PCA) and the KarhunenÔÇôLo├Ęve transform (KL-transform).
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The covariance matrix plays a key role in financial economics, especially in portfolio theory and its mutual fund separation theorem and in the capital asset pricing model.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The matrix of covariances among various assets' returns is used to determine, under certain assumptions, the relative amounts of different assets that investors should (in a normative analysis) or are predicted to (in a positive analysis) choose to hold in a context of diversification.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The evolution strategy, a particular family of Randomized Search Heuristics, fundamentally relies on a covariance matrix in its mechanism.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The characteristic mutation operator draws the update step from a multivariate normal distribution using an evolving covariance matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Intuitively, this result is supported by the rationale that the optimal covariance distribution can offer mutation steps whose equidensity probability contours match the level sets of the landscape, and so they maximize the progress rate.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] In **covariance mapping** the values of the $\operatorname {cov} (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} )$ or $\operatorname {pcov} (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} \mid \mathbf {I} )$ matrix are plotted as a 2-dimensional map.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] When vectors $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ are discrete random functions, the map shows statistical relations between different regions of the random functions.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Statistically independent regions of the functions show up on the map as zero-level flatland, while positive or negative correlations show up, respectively, as hills or valleys.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] 1 illustrates how a partial covariance map is constructed on an example of an experiment performed at the FLASH free-electron laser in Hamburg.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The random function $X(t)$ is the time-of-flight spectrum of ions from a Coulomb explosion of nitrogen molecules multiply ionised by a laser pulse.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Since only a few hundreds of molecules are ionised at each laser pulse, the single-shot spectra are highly fluctuating.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] However, collecting typically $m=10^{4}$ such spectra, $\mathbf {X} _{j}(t)$ , and averaging them over j produces a smooth spectrum $\langle \mathbf {X} (t)\rangle$ , which is shown in red at the bottom of Fig.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The average spectrum $\langle \mathbf {X} \rangle$ reveals several nitrogen ions in a form of peaks broadened by their kinetic energy, but to find the correlations between the ionisation stages and the ion momenta requires calculating a covariance map.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] 1 spectra $\mathbf {X} _{j}(t)$ and $\mathbf {Y} _{j}(t)$ are the same, except that the range of the time-of-flight t differs.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Panel **a** shows $\langle \mathbf {XY^{\mathsf {T}}} \rangle$ , panel **b** shows $\langle \mathbf {X} \rangle \langle \mathbf {Y} ^{\mathsf {T}}\rangle$ and panel **c** shows their difference, which is $\operatorname {cov} (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} )$ (note a change in the colour scale).
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Unfortunately, this map is overwhelmed by uninteresting, common-mode correlations induced by laser intensity fluctuating from shot to shot.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] To suppress such correlations the laser intensity $I_{j}$ is recorded at every shot, put into $\mathbf {I}$ and $\operatorname {pcov} (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} \mid \mathbf {I} )$ is calculated as panels **d** and **e** show.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] The suppression of the uninteresting correlations is, however, imperfect because there are other sources of common-mode fluctuations than the laser intensity and in principle all these sources should be monitored in vector $\mathbf {I}$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Yet in practice it is often sufficient to overcompensate the partial covariance correction as panel **f** shows, where interesting correlations of ion momenta are now clearly visible as straight lines centred on ionisation stages of atomic nitrogen.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy employs correlation analysis to obtain 2D spectra of the condensed phase.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] There are two versions of this analysis: synchronous and asynchronous.
[src:principal-component-analysis/covariance-matrix] Mathematically, the former is expressed in terms of the sample covariance matrix and the technique is equivalent to covariance mapping.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Methods are commonly divided into linear and nonlinear approaches.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Linear approaches can be further divided into feature selection and feature extraction.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Dimensionality reduction can be used for noise reduction, data visualization, cluster analysis, or as an intermediate step to facilitate other analyses.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] The process of feature selection aims to find a suitable subset of the input variables (*features*, or *attributes*) for the task at hand.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] The three strategies are: the *filter* strategy (e.g., information gain), the *wrapper* strategy (e.g., accuracy-guided search), and the *embedded* strategy (features are added or removed while building the model based on prediction errors).
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Data analysis such as regression or classification can be done in the reduced space more accurately than in the original space.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Feature projection (also called feature extraction) transforms the data from the high-dimensional space to a space of fewer dimensions.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] The data transformation may be linear, as in principal component analysis (PCA), but many nonlinear dimensionality reduction techniques also exist.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] For multidimensional data, tensor representation can be used in dimensionality reduction through multilinear subspace learning.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] The main linear technique for dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis, performs a linear mapping of the data to a lower-dimensional space in such a way that the variance of the data in the low-dimensional representation is maximized.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] In practice, the covariance (and sometimes the correlation) matrix of the data is constructed and the eigenvectors on this matrix are computed.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] The eigenvectors that correspond to the largest eigenvalues (the principal components) can now be used to reconstruct a large fraction of the variance of the original data.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Moreover, the first few eigenvectors can often be interpreted in terms of the large-scale physical behavior of the system, because they often contribute the vast majority of the system's energy, especially in low-dimensional systems.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Still, this must be proved on a case-by-case basis as not all systems exhibit this behavior.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] The original space (with dimension of the number of points) has been reduced (with data loss, but hopefully retaining the most important variance) to the space spanned by a few eigenvectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] NMF decomposes a non-negative matrix to the product of two non-negative ones, which has been a promising tool in fields where only non-negative signals exist, such as astronomy.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] With a stable component basis during construction, and a linear modeling process, sequential NMF is able to preserve the flux in direct imaging of circumstellar structures in astronomy, as one of the methods of detecting exoplanets, especially for the direct imaging of circumstellar discs.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] In comparison with PCA, NMF does not remove the mean of the matrices, which leads to physical non-negative fluxes; therefore NMF is able to preserve more information than PCA as demonstrated by Ren et al.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Principal component analysis can be employed in a nonlinear way by means of the kernel trick.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is capable of constructing nonlinear mappings that maximize the variance in the data.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is called kernel PCA.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Other prominent nonlinear techniques include manifold learning techniques such as Isomap, locally linear embedding (LLE), Hessian LLE, Laplacian eigenmaps, and methods based on tangent space analysis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] More recently, techniques have been proposed that, instead of defining a fixed kernel, try to learn the kernel using semidefinite programming.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] The most prominent example of such a technique is maximum variance unfolding (MVU).
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] The central idea of MVU is to exactly preserve all pairwise distances between nearest neighbors (in the inner product space) while maximizing the distances between points that are not nearest neighbors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] An alternative approach to neighborhood preservation is through the minimization of a cost function that measures differences between distances in the input and output spaces.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] A different approach to nonlinear dimensionality reduction is through the use of autoencoders, a special kind of feedforward neural networks with a bottleneck hidden layer.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] The training of deep encoders is typically performed using a greedy layer-wise pre-training (e.g., using a stack of restricted Boltzmann machines) that is followed by a finetuning stage based on backpropagation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is a generalization of Fisher's linear discriminant, a method used in statistics, pattern recognition, and machine learning to find a linear combination of features that characterizes or separates two or more classes of objects or events.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] GDA deals with nonlinear discriminant analysis using kernel function operator.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] The underlying theory is close to the support-vector machines (SVM) insofar as the GDA method provides a mapping of the input vectors into high-dimensional feature space.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Similar to LDA, the objective of GDA is to find a projection for the features into a lower dimensional space by maximizing the ratio of between-class scatter to within-class scatter.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Autoencoders can be used to learn nonlinear dimension reduction functions and codings together with an inverse function from the coding to the original representation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique useful for the visualization of high-dimensional datasets.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] It is not recommended for use in analysis such as clustering or outlier detection since it does not necessarily preserve densities or distances well.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] Visually, it is similar to t-SNE, but it assumes that the data is uniformly distributed on a locally connected Riemannian manifold and that the Riemannian metric is locally constant or approximately locally constant.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] For high-dimensional datasets, dimension reduction is usually performed prior to applying a *k*-nearest neighbors (*k*-NN) algorithm in order to mitigate the curse of dimensionality.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] In machine learning, this process is also called low-dimensional embedding.
[src:principal-component-analysis/dimensionality-reduction] A dimensionality reduction technique that is sometimes used in neuroscience is maximally informative dimensions, which finds a lower-dimensional representation of a dataset such that as much information as possible about the original data is preserved.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In linear algebra, an **eigenvector** (/╦ła╔¬╔í╔Ön-/ *EYE-g╔Ön-*) or **characteristic vector** is a (nonzero) vector that has its direction unchanged (or reversed) by a given linear transformation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] More precisely, an eigenvector $\mathbf {v}$ of a linear transformation T is scaled by a constant factor $\lambda$ when the linear transformation is applied to it: Ôüá $T\mathbf {v} =\lambda \mathbf {v}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The corresponding **eigenvalue**, **characteristic value**, or **characteristic root** is the multiplying factor $\lambda$ (possibly a negative or complex number).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Geometrically, vectors are multi-dimensional quantities with magnitude and direction, often pictured as arrows.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A linear transformation rotates, stretches, or shears the vectors upon which it acts.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A linear transformation's eigenvectors are those vectors that are only stretched or shrunk, with neither rotation nor shear.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The corresponding eigenvalue is the factor by which an eigenvector is stretched or shrunk.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If the eigenvalue is negative, then the eigenvector's direction is reversed.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvectors and eigenvalues of a linear transformation serve to characterize it, and so they play important roles in all areas where linear algebra is applied, from geology to quantum mechanics.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In particular, it is often the case that a system is represented by a linear transformation whose outputs are fed as inputs to the same transformation (feedback).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In such an application, the largest eigenvalue is of particular importance, because it governs the long-term behavior of the system after many applications of the linear transformation, and the associated eigenvector is the steady state of the system.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This relationship can be expressed as: Ôüá $A\mathbf {v} =\lambda \mathbf {v}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Given an Ôüá n Ôüá-dimensional vector space and a choice of basis, there is a direct correspondence between linear transformations from the vector space into itself and Ôüá $n\times n$ Ôüá square matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Hence, in a finite-dimensional vector space, it is equivalent to define eigenvalues and eigenvectors using either the language of linear transformations, or the language of matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Eigenvalues and eigenvectors feature prominently in the analysis of linear transformations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The prefix *eigen-* is adopted from the German *eigen* (cognate with the English word *own*) for 'proper', 'characteristic', 'own'.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Originally used to study principal axes of the rotational motion of rigid bodies, eigenvalues and eigenvectors have a wide range of applications, for example in stability analysis, vibration analysis, atomic orbitals, facial recognition, and matrix diagonalization.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In essence, an eigenvector **v** of a linear transformation T is a nonzero vector that, when T is applied to it, does not change direction.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Applying T to the eigenvector only scales the eigenvector by the scalar value ╬╗, called an eigenvalue.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This condition can be written as the equation $T(\mathbf {v} )=\lambda \mathbf {v} ,$ referred to as the **eigenvalue equation** or **eigenequation**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] For example, ╬╗ may be negative, in which case the eigenvector reverses direction as part of the scaling, or it may be zero, or complex.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The example here, based on the Mona Lisa, provides a simple illustration.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Each point on the painting can be represented as a vector pointing from the center of the painting to that point.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The linear transformation in this example is called a shear mapping.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Points in the top half are moved to the right, and points in the bottom half are moved to the left, proportional to how far they are from the horizontal axis that goes through the middle of the painting.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The vectors pointing to each point in the original image are therefore tilted right or left, and made longer or shorter by the transformation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Points *along* the horizontal axis do not move at all when this transformation is applied.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore, any vector that points directly to the right or left with no vertical component is an eigenvector of this transformation, because the mapping does not change its direction.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Moreover, these eigenvectors all have an eigenvalue equal to one, because the mapping does not change their length either.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Linear transformations can take many different forms, mapping vectors in a variety of vector spaces, so the eigenvectors can also take many forms.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If the linear transformation is expressed in the form of an n ├Ś n matrix A, then the eigenvalue equation for a linear transformation above can be rewritten as the matrix multiplication $A\mathbf {v} =\lambda \mathbf {v} ,$ where the eigenvector **v** is an n ├Ś 1 matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] For a matrix, eigenvalues and eigenvectors can be used to decompose the matrix; for example, by diagonalizing it.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Additional animations of eigenvectors and eigenvalues in two dimensions, including symmetric transformations and transformations with complex eigenvalues, are available at Wikimedia Commons.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Eigenvalues are often introduced in the context of linear algebra or matrix theory.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Historically, however, they arose in the study of quadratic forms and differential equations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In the 18th century, Leonhard Euler studied the rotational motion of a rigid body, and discovered the importance of the principal axes.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Joseph-Louis Lagrange realized that the principal axes are the eigenvectors of the inertia matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In the early 19th century, Augustin-Louis Cauchy saw how their work could be used to classify the quadric surfaces, and generalized it to arbitrary dimensions.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Cauchy also coined the term *racine caract├ęristique* (characteristic root), for what is now called *eigenvalue*; his term survives in *characteristic equation*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Later, Joseph Fourier used the work of Lagrange and Pierre-Simon Laplace to solve the heat equation by separation of variables in his 1822 treatise *The Analytic Theory of Heat (Th├ęorie analytique de la chaleur)*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Charles-Fran├žois Sturm elaborated on Fourier's ideas further, and brought them to the attention of Cauchy, who combined them with his own ideas and arrived at the fact that real symmetric matrices have real eigenvalues.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This was extended by Charles Hermite in 1855 to what are now called Hermitian matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Around the same time, Francesco Brioschi proved that the eigenvalues of orthogonal matrices lie on the unit circle, and Alfred Clebsch found the corresponding result for skew-symmetric matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Finally, Karl Weierstrass clarified an important aspect in the stability theory started by Laplace, by realizing that defective matrices can cause instability.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In the meantime, Joseph Liouville studied eigenvalue problems similar to those of Sturm; the discipline that grew out of their work is now called *SturmÔÇôLiouville theory*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Schwarz studied the first eigenvalue of Laplace's equation on general domains towards the end of the 19th century, while Poincar├ę studied Poisson's equation a few years later.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] At the start of the 20th century, David Hilbert studied the eigenvalues of integral operators by viewing the operators as infinite matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] He was the first to use the German word *eigen*, which means "own", to denote eigenvalues and eigenvectors in 1904, though he may have been following a related usage by Hermann von Helmholtz.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] For some time, the standard term in English was "proper value", but the more distinctive term "eigenvalue" is the standard today.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The first numerical algorithm for computing eigenvalues and eigenvectors appeared in 1929, when Richard von Mises published the power method.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] One of the most popular methods today, the QR algorithm, was proposed independently by John G.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Eigenvalues and eigenvectors are often introduced to students in the context of linear algebra courses focused on matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Furthermore, linear transformations over a finite-dimensional vector space can be represented using matrices, which is especially common in numerical and computational applications.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] then Ôüá $\mathbf {v}$ Ôüá is an **eigenvector** of the linear transformation Ôüá A Ôüá and the scale factor Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá is the **eigenvalue** corresponding to that eigenvector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Equation (**1**) is the **eigenvalue equation** for the matrix Ôüá A Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] where Ôüá I Ôüá is the Ôüá $n\times n$ Ôüá identity matrix and Ôüá $\mathbf {0}$ Ôüá is the zero vector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Equation (**2**) has a nonzero solution v if and only if the determinant of the matrix (*A* Ôłĺ *╬╗I*) is zero.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Using the Leibniz formula for determinants, the left-hand side of equation (**3**) is a polynomial function of the variable ╬╗ and the degree of this polynomial is n, the order of the matrix A.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Its coefficients depend on the entries of A, except that its term of degree n is always (Ôłĺ1)*n**╬╗**n*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This polynomial is called the *characteristic polynomial* of A.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Equation (**3**) is called the *characteristic equation* or *secular equation* of A.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The characteristic polynomial of an n-by-n matrix A, being a polynomial of degree n, has at most n complex number roots, which can be found by factoring the characteristic polynomial, or numerically by root finding.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] where the complex numbers *╬╗*1, *╬╗*2, ..., *╬╗**n*, each of which is an eigenvalue, may repeat.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvectors corresponding to each eigenvalue ╬╗ can be found by solving for the components of **v** in the equation (*A* Ôłĺ *╬╗I*)**v** = **0**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If the entries of the matrix A are all real numbers, then the coefficients of the characteristic polynomial will also be real numbers, but the eigenvalues may still have nonzero imaginary parts.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The entries of the corresponding eigenvectors therefore may also have nonzero imaginary parts.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Similarly, the eigenvalues may be irrational numbers even if all the entries of A are rational numbers or even if they are all integers.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] However, if the entries of A are all algebraic numbers, which include the rationals, then the eigenvalues must also be algebraic numbers.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The non-real roots of a real polynomial with real coefficients can be grouped into pairs of complex conjugates, namely with the two members of each pair having imaginary parts that differ only in sign and the same real part.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If the degree is odd, then by the intermediate value theorem at least one of the roots is real.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore, any real matrix with odd order has at least one real eigenvalue, whereas a real matrix with even order may not have any real eigenvalues.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvectors associated with these complex eigenvalues are also complex and also appear in complex conjugate pairs.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The **spectrum** of a matrix is the list of its eigenvalues, repeated according to their multiplicities; in a shorter notation, the set of its eigenvalues with their multiplicities indicated.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] An important quantity associated with the spectrum of a matrix is the maximum absolute value of all of its eigenvalues.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This is known as the spectral radius of the considered matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Let *╬╗**i* be an eigenvalue of an n-by-n matrix A.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The **algebraic multiplicity** *╬╝**A*(*╬╗**i*) of the eigenvalue is its multiplicity as a root of the characteristic polynomial, that is, the largest integer k such that (*╬╗**i* Ôłĺ *╬╗*)*k* evenly divides that polynomial.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Suppose a matrix A has order n and *d* ÔëĄ *n* distinct eigenvalues.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The size of each eigenvalue's algebraic multiplicity is related to the dimension n as ${\begin{aligned}1&\leq \mu _{A}(\lambda _{i})\leq n,\\\mu _{A}&=\sum _{i=1}^{d}\mu _{A}\left(\lambda _{i}\right)=n.\end{aligned}}$ If *╬╝**A*(*╬╗**i*) = 1, then ╬╗i is said to be a **simple eigenvalue**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If *╬╝**A*(*╬╗**i*) equals the geometric multiplicity of ╬╗i (denoted by *╬│**A*(*╬╗**i*) and defined in the next section), then ╬╗i is said to be a **semisimple eigenvalue**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Given a particular eigenvalue Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá of the Ôüá $n\times n$ Ôüá matrix Ôüá A Ôüá, define the set Ôüá E Ôüá to be all vectors Ôüá $\mathbf {v}$ Ôüá that satisfy equation (**2**): $E=\left\{\mathbf {v$ On one hand, Ôüá E Ôüá is precisely the *kernel* or *nullspace* of the matrix Ôüá $A-\lambda I$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] On the other hand, by definition, any nonzero vector that satisfies this condition is an eigenvector of Ôüá A Ôüá associated with Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá; so Ôüá E Ôüá is the union of the zero vector with the set of all eigenvectors of Ôüá A Ôüá associated with Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The space Ôüá E Ôüá is called the **eigenspace** or **characteristic space** of Ôüá A Ôüá associated with Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In general, Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá is a complex number and the eigenvectors are complex Ôüá $n\times 1$ Ôüá matrices (column vectors).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Because every nullspace is a linear subspace of the domain, Ôüá E Ôüá is a linear subspace of Ôüá $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Because the eigenspace Ôüá E Ôüá is a linear subspace, it is closed under addition.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] That is, if two vectors Ôüá $\mathbf {u}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {v}$ Ôüá belong to the set Ôüá E Ôüá, written Ôüá $\mathbf {u} ,\mathbf {v} \in E$ Ôüá, then Ôüá $\mathbf {u} +\mathbf {v} \in E$ Ôüá, or equivalently Ôüá $A(\mathbf {u} +\mathbf {v} )=\lambda (\mathbf {u} +\mathbf {v} )$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This can be checked using the distributive property of matrix multiplication.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Similarly, because Ôüá E Ôüá is a linear subspace, it is closed under scalar multiplication.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] That is, if Ôüá $\mathbf {v} \in E$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\alpha \in \mathbb {C}$ Ôüá, then Ôüá $\alpha \mathbf {v} \in E$ Ôüá, or equivalently Ôüá $A(\alpha \mathbf {v} )=\lambda (\alpha \mathbf {v} )$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This can be checked by noting that multiplication of complex matrices by complex numbers is commutative.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] As long as Ôüá $\mathbf {u} +\mathbf {v}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\alpha \mathbf {v}$ Ôüá are not zero, they are also eigenvectors of Ôüá A Ôüá associated with Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The dimension of the eigenspace Ôüá E Ôüá associated with Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá, or equivalently the maximum number of linearly independent eigenvectors associated with Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá, is referred to as the eigenvalue's **geometric multiplicity** and denoted by Ôüá $\gamma _{A}(\lambda )$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Because Ôüá E Ôüá is also the nullspace of Ôüá $A-\lambda I$ Ôüá, the geometric multiplicity of Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá is the dimension of the nullspace of Ôüá $A-\lambda I$ Ôüá, also called the **nullity** of Ôüá $A-\lambda I$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Furthermore, an eigenvalue's geometric multiplicity cannot exceed its algebraic multiplicity.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Additionally, recall that an eigenvalue's algebraic multiplicity cannot exceed Ôüá n Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Proof of inequality Ôüá $\gamma _{A}(\lambda )\leq \mu _{A}(\lambda )$ Ôüá: Let *B* = *A* Ôłĺ *╬╗I*, where ╬╗ is a fixed complex number, and the eigenspace associated with ╬╗ is the nullspace of B.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Let the dimension of that eigenspace be Ôüá $k=\gamma _{A}(\lambda )$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This means that the last k rows of the echelon form of B are zero.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Thus, there is an invertible matrix E coming from Gauss-Jordan reduction, such that $EB={\begin{bmatrix}*&*\\\mathbf {0} _{k\times (n-k)}&\mathbf {0} _{k\times k}\end{bmatrix}}.$ Therefore the last k rows of *EB* Ôłĺ *tE* are (Ôłĺ*t*) times the last k rows of E.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore the polynomial tk evenly divides the polynomial det(*EB* Ôłĺ *tE*), because of basic properties of determinants (homogeneity).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] On the other hand, det(*EB* Ôłĺ *tE*) = det *E* det(*B* Ôłĺ *tI*) = *pA*(*t* + *╬╗*) det *E*, so (*t* Ôłĺ *╬╗*)*k* divides *pA*(*t*), and so the algebraic multiplicity of ╬╗ is at least Ôüá k Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Suppose A has *d* ÔëĄ *n* distinct eigenvalues *╬╗*1, ..., *╬╗**d*, where the geometric multiplicity of ╬╗i is *╬│A*(*╬╗i*).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The total geometric multiplicity of A, $\gamma _{A}=\sum _{i=1}^{d}\gamma _{A}(\lambda _{i}),$ is the dimension of the sum of all the eigenspaces of A's eigenvalues, or equivalently the maximum number of linearly independent eigenvectors of A.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] By construction, Ôüá $d\leq \gamma _{A}\leq n$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Let A be an arbitrary n ├Ś n matrix of complex numbers with eigenvalues *╬╗*1, ..., *╬╗n*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Each eigenvalue appears *╬╝A*(*╬╗i*) times in this list, where *╬╝A*(*╬╗i*) is the eigenvalue's algebraic multiplicity.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Many disciplines traditionally represent vectors as matrices with a single column rather than as matrices with a single row.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In this formulation, the defining equation is $\mathbf {u} A=\kappa \mathbf {u} ,$ where ╬║ is a scalar and **u** is a 1 ├Ś n matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Any row vector **u** satisfying this equation is called a '**left eigenvector**' of A, and ╬║ is still called its associated eigenvalue.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Comparing this equation to equation (**1**), it follows immediately that a left eigenvector of Ôüá A Ôüá is the same as the transpose of a right eigenvector of Ôüá $A^{\mathsf {T}}$ Ôüá, with the same eigenvalue.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Furthermore, since the characteristic polynomial of Ôüá $A^{\mathsf {T}}$ Ôüá is the same as the characteristic polynomial of Ôüá A Ôüá, the left and right eigenvectors of Ôüá A Ôüá are associated with the same eigenvalues.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A matrix has the same eigenvalues as its transpose, as can be directly seen as follows.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Assume Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá is an eigenvalue of an Ôüá $n\times n$ Ôüá matrix Ôüá A Ôüá with eigenvector Ôüá x Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Thus, the columns of Ôüá $(A-\lambda I)$ Ôüá are linearly dependent.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Equivalently, the rank of the matrix is less than Ôüá n Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] But as column rank = row rank, the rows are also linearly dependent.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Moreover, Ôüá $y^{\mathsf {T}}$ Ôüá is not the zero vector; so Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá is also an eigenvalue of Ôüá $A^{\mathsf {T}}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Furthermore, this argument shows that the eigenvalues of A and $A^{\mathsf {T}}$ have the same geometric multiplicity (since column nullity = row nullity).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Suppose the eigenvectors of A form a basis of Ôüá $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ Ôüá, or equivalently A has n linearly independent eigenvectors **v**1, **v**2, ..., **v***n* (with associated eigenvalues *╬╗*1, *╬╗*2, ..., *╬╗**n*).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvectors need not be orthogonal to one another, and the eigenvalues need not be distinct.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] With this in mind, define the diagonal matrix ╬Ť where each diagonal element ╬Ťii is the eigenvalue associated with the ith column of Q.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Then $AQ=Q\varLambda .$ Because the columns of Q are linearly independent, Q is invertible.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This is called the eigendecomposition; it is a similarity transformation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Such a matrix A is said to be **similar** to the diagonal matrix ╬Ť, or *diagonalizable*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The matrix Q is the change of basis matrix of the similarity transformation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Essentially, the matrices A and ╬Ť represent the same linear transformation expressed in two different bases.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvectors are used as the basis when representing the linear transformation as ╬Ť.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Conversely, suppose a matrix A is diagonalizable.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Let P be a non-singular square matrix such that *P*Ôłĺ1*AP* is some diagonal matrix D.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Left multiplying both by P yields *AP* = *PD*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Each column of P must therefore be an eigenvector of A whose eigenvalue is the corresponding diagonal element of D.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Since the columns of P must be linearly independent for P to be invertible, there exist n linearly independent eigenvectors of A.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In conclusion, the eigenvectors of Ôüá A Ôüá form a basis of Ôüá $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ Ôüá if and only if Ôüá A Ôüá is diagonalizable.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A matrix that is not diagonalizable is said to be *defective*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] For defective matrices, the notion of eigenvectors generalizes to generalized eigenvectors and the diagonal matrix of eigenvalues generalizes to the Jordan normal form.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Over an algebraically closed field, any matrix A has a Jordan normal form and therefore admits a basis of generalized eigenvectors and a decomposition into generalized eigenspaces.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In the Hermitian case, eigenvalues can be given a variational characterization.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The largest eigenvalue of H is the maximum value of the quadratic form **x**T*H***x**/**x**T**x**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A value of **x** that realizes that maximum is an eigenvector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Consider the matrix $A={\begin{bmatrix}2&1\\1&2\end{bmatrix}}.$ The figure on the right shows the effect of this transformation on point coordinates in the plane.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvectors v of this transformation satisfy equation (**1**), and the values of ╬╗ for which the determinant of the matrix (*A* Ôłĺ *╬╗I*) equals zero are the eigenvalues.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore, $\mathbf {v} _{\lambda =1}={\begin{bmatrix}v_{1}\\-v_{1}\end{bmatrix}}={\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix}}$ is an eigenvector of A corresponding to *╬╗* = 1, as is any scalar multiple of this vector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore, $\mathbf {v} _{\lambda =3}={\begin{bmatrix}v_{1}\\v_{1}\end{bmatrix}}={\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\end{bmatrix}}$ is an eigenvector of A corresponding to *╬╗* = 3, as is any scalar multiple of this vector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Thus, the vectors **v***╬╗*=1 and **v***╬╗*=3 are eigenvectors of A associated with the eigenvalues *╬╗* = 1 and *╬╗* = 3, respectively.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The roots of the characteristic polynomial are 2, 1, and 11, which are the only three eigenvalues of A.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] These eigenvalues correspond to the eigenvectors [1 0 0]T, [0 Ôłĺ2 1]T, and [0 1 2]T, or any nonzero multiple thereof.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This matrix shifts the coordinates of the vector up by one position and moves the first coordinate to the bottom.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] For the real eigenvalue *╬╗*1 = 1, any vector with three equal nonzero entries is an eigenvector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore, the other two eigenvectors of A are complex and are **v***╬╗*2 = [1 *╬╗*2 *╬╗*3]T and **v***╬╗*3 = [1 *╬╗*3 *╬╗*2]T with eigenvalues *╬╗*2 and *╬╗*3, respectively.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Matrices with entries only along the main diagonal are called *diagonal matrices*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvalues of a diagonal matrix are the diagonal elements themselves.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] These roots are the diagonal elements as well as the eigenvalues of A.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Each diagonal element corresponds to an eigenvector whose only nonzero component is in the same row as that diagonal element.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A matrix whose elements above the main diagonal are all zero is called a *lower triangular matrix*, while a matrix whose elements below the main diagonal are all zero is called an *upper triangular matrix*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] As with diagonal matrices, the eigenvalues of triangular matrices are the elements of the main diagonal.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The roots of this polynomial, and hence the eigenvalues, are 2 and 3.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The **algebraic multiplicity** of each eigenvalue is 2; in other words they are both double roots.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The sum of the algebraic multiplicities of all distinct eigenvalues is *╬╝**A* = 4 = *n*, the order of the characteristic polynomial and the dimension of A.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] On the other hand, the **geometric multiplicity** of the eigenvalue 2 is only 1, because its eigenspace is spanned by just one vector [0 1 Ôłĺ1 1]T and is therefore 1-dimensional.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Similarly, the geometric multiplicity of the eigenvalue 3 is 1 because its eigenspace is spanned by just one vector [0 0 0 1]T.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The total geometric multiplicity *╬│**A* is 2, which is the smallest it could be for a matrix with two distinct eigenvalues.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Geometric multiplicities are defined in a later section.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This identity also extends to diagonalizable matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] It has been discovered in and rediscovered many times in the literature (see, e.g., ).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The definitions of eigenvalue and eigenvectors of a linear transformation T remains valid even if the underlying vector space is an infinite-dimensional Hilbert or Banach space.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] A widely used class of linear transformations acting on infinite-dimensional spaces are the differential operators on function spaces.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Let D be a linear differential operator on the space $C^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} )$ of infinitely differentiable real functions of a real argument t.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenvalue equation for D is the differential equation $Df(t)=\lambda f(t)$ The functions that satisfy this equation are eigenvectors of D and are commonly called '**eigenfunctions**'.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Consider the derivative operator ${\tfrac {d}{dt}}$ with eigenvalue equation ${\frac {d}{dt}}f(t)=\lambda f(t).$ This differential equation can be solved by multiplying both sides by *dt*/*f*(*t*) and integrating.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Its solution, the exponential function $f(t)=f(0)e^{\lambda t},$ is the eigenfunction of the derivative operator.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In this case the eigenfunction is itself a function of its associated eigenvalue.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In particular, for *╬╗* = 0 the eigenfunction *f*(*t*) is a constant.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The concept of eigenvalues and eigenvectors extends naturally to arbitrary linear transformations on arbitrary vector spaces.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] This equation is called the eigenvalue equation for T, and the scalar ╬╗ is the **eigenvalue** of T corresponding to the eigenvector **v**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] *T*(**v**) is the result of applying the transformation T to the vector **v**, while *╬╗***v** is the product of the scalar ╬╗ with **v**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Given an eigenvalue ╬╗, consider the set $E=\left\{\mathbf {v} :T(\mathbf {v} )=\lambda \mathbf {v} \right\},$ which is the union of the zero vector with the set of all eigenvectors associated with ╬╗.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] E is called the '**eigenspace**' or '**characteristic space**' of T associated with ╬╗.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] It is the kernel of the linear transformation *T* Ôłĺ *╬╗I*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenspace E associated with ╬╗ is therefore a linear subspace of V.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If that subspace has dimension 1, it is sometimes called an '**eigenline**'.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The '**geometric multiplicity**' *╬│**T*(*╬╗*) of an eigenvalue ╬╗ is the dimension of the eigenspace associated with ╬╗, i.e., the maximum number of linearly independent eigenvectors associated with that eigenvalue.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] By the definition of eigenvalues and eigenvectors, *╬│**T*(*╬╗*) Ôëą 1 because every eigenvalue has at least one eigenvector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The eigenspaces of T always form a direct sum.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] As a consequence, eigenvectors of *different* eigenvalues are always linearly independent.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Therefore, the sum of the dimensions of the eigenspaces cannot exceed the dimension n of the vector space on which T operates, and there cannot be more than n distinct eigenvalues.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Any subspace spanned by eigenvectors of T is an invariant subspace of T, and the restriction of T to such a subspace is diagonalizable.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] When T admits an eigenbasis, T is diagonalizable.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] If ╬╗ is an eigenvalue of T, then the operator (*T* Ôłĺ *╬╗I*) is not one-to-one, and therefore its inverse (*T* Ôłĺ *╬╗I*)Ôłĺ1 does not exist.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The converse is true for finite-dimensional vector spaces, but not for infinite-dimensional vector spaces.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] In general, the operator (*T* Ôłĺ *╬╗I*) may not have an inverse even if ╬╗ is not an eigenvalue.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] For this reason, in functional analysis eigenvalues can be generalized to the spectrum of a linear operator T as the set of all scalars ╬╗ for which the operator (*T* Ôłĺ *╬╗I*) has no bounded inverse.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The spectrum of an operator always contains all its eigenvalues but is not limited to them.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] One can generalize the algebraic object that is acting on the vector space, replacing a single operator acting on a vector space with an algebra representation ÔÇô an associative algebra acting on a module.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The study of such actions is the field of representation theory.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] The representation-theoretical concept of weight is an analog of eigenvalues, while *weight vectors* and *weight spaces* are the analogs of eigenvectors and eigenspaces, respectively.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p01] Hecke eigensheaf is a tensor-multiple of itself and is considered in Langlands correspondence.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The calculation of eigenvalues and eigenvectors is a topic where theory, as presented in elementary linear algebra textbooks, is often very far from practice.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The classical method is to first find the eigenvalues, and then calculate the eigenvectors for each eigenvalue.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] It is in several ways poorly suited for non-exact arithmetics such as floating-point.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigenvalues of a matrix A can be determined by finding the roots of the characteristic polynomial.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] This is easy for 2 ├Ś 2 matrices, but the difficulty increases rapidly with the size of the matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In theory, the coefficients of the characteristic polynomial can be computed exactly, since they are sums of products of matrix elements; and there are algorithms that can find all the roots of a polynomial of arbitrary degree to any required accuracy.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] However, this approach is not viable in practice because the coefficients would be contaminated by unavoidable round-off errors, and the roots of a polynomial can be an extremely sensitive function of the coefficients (as exemplified by Wilkinson's polynomial).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Even for matrices whose elements are integers the calculation becomes nontrivial, because the sums are very long; the constant term is the determinant, which for an n ├Ś n matrix is a sum of *n*! different products.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Explicit algebraic formulas for the roots of a polynomial exist only if the degree n is 4 or less.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] According to the AbelÔÇôRuffini theorem there is no general, explicit and exact algebraic formula for the roots of a polynomial with degree 5 or more.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Even the exact formula for the roots of a degree 3 polynomial is numerically impractical.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Once the (exact) value of an eigenvalue is known, the corresponding eigenvectors can be found by finding nonzero solutions of the eigenvalue equation, that becomes a system of linear equations with known coefficients.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Both equations reduce to the single linear equation *y* = 2*x*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Therefore, any vector of the form [*a* 2*a*]T, for any nonzero real number a, is an eigenvector of A with eigenvalue *╬╗* = 6.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The matrix A above has another eigenvalue *╬╗* = 1.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A similar calculation shows that the corresponding eigenvectors are the nonzero solutions of 3*x* + *y* = 0, that is, any vector of the form [*b* Ôłĺ3*b*]T, for any nonzero real number b.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The converse approach, of first seeking the eigenvectors and then determining each eigenvalue from its eigenvector, turns out to be far more tractable for computers.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The easiest algorithm here consists of picking an arbitrary starting vector and then repeatedly multiplying it with the matrix (optionally normalizing the vector to keep its elements of reasonable size); this makes the vector converge towards an eigenvector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A variation is to instead multiply the vector by (*A* Ôłĺ *╬╝I*)Ôłĺ1; this causes it to converge to an eigenvector of the eigenvalue closest to $\mu \in \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] If **v** is (a good approximation of) an eigenvector of A, then the corresponding eigenvalue can be computed as $\lambda ={\frac {\mathbf {v} ^{*}A\mathbf {v} }{\mathbf {v} ^{*}\mathbf {v} }}$ where **v**ÔłŚ denotes the conjugate transpose of **v**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Efficient, accurate methods to compute eigenvalues and eigenvectors of arbitrary matrices were not known until the QR algorithm was designed in 1961.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Combining the Householder transformation with the LU decomposition results in an algorithm with better convergence than the QR algorithm.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] For large Hermitian sparse matrices, the Lanczos algorithm is one example of an efficient iterative method to compute eigenvalues and eigenvectors, among several other possibilities.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Most numeric methods that compute the eigenvalues of a matrix also determine a set of corresponding eigenvectors as a by-product of the computation, although sometimes implementors choose to discard the eigenvector information as soon as it is no longer needed.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Eigenvectors and eigenvalues can be useful for understanding linear transformations of geometric shapes.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The following table presents some example transformations in the plane along with their 2 ├Ś 2 matrices, eigenvalues, and eigenvectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The characteristic equation for a rotation is a quadratic equation with discriminant *D* = Ôłĺ4(sin *╬Ş*)2, which is a negative number whenever ╬Ş is not an integer multiple of ¤Ç (180┬░).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Therefore, except for these special cases, the two eigenvalues are complex numbers, cos *╬Ş* ┬▒ *i*sin *╬Ş*; and all eigenvectors have non-real entries.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Indeed, except for those special cases, a rotation changes the direction of every nonzero vector in the plane.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A linear transformation that takes a square to a rectangle of the same area (a squeeze mapping) has reciprocal eigenvalues.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigendecomposition of a symmetric positive semidefinite (PSD) matrix yields an orthogonal basis of eigenvectors, each of which has a nonnegative eigenvalue.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The orthogonal decomposition of a PSD matrix is used in multivariate analysis, where the sample covariance matrices are PSD.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] This orthogonal decomposition is called principal component analysis (PCA) in statistics.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] PCA studies linear relations among variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] PCA is performed on the covariance matrix or the correlation matrix (in which each variable is scaled to have its sample variance equal to one).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] For the covariance or correlation matrix, the eigenvectors correspond to principal components and the eigenvalues to the variance explained by the principal components.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Principal component analysis of the correlation matrix provides an orthogonal basis for the space of the observed data: In this basis, the largest eigenvalues correspond to the principal components that are associated with most of the covariability among a number of observed data.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Principal component analysis is used as a means of dimensionality reduction in the study of large data sets, such as those encountered in bioinformatics.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In Q methodology, the eigenvalues of the correlation matrix determine the Q-methodologist's judgment of *practical* significance (which differs from the statistical significance of hypothesis testing; cf. criteria for determining the number of factors).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] More generally, principal component analysis can be used as a method of factor analysis in structural equation modeling.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The kth principal eigenvector of a graph is defined as either the eigenvector corresponding to the kth largest or kth smallest eigenvalue of the Laplacian.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The first principal eigenvector of the graph is also referred to merely as the principal eigenvector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The principal eigenvector is used to measure the centrality of its vertices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] An example is Google's PageRank algorithm.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The principal eigenvector of a modified adjacency matrix of the World Wide Web graph gives the page ranks as its components.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] This vector corresponds to the stationary distribution of the Markov chain represented by the row-normalized adjacency matrix; however, the adjacency matrix must first be modified to ensure a stationary distribution exists.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The second smallest eigenvector can be used to partition the graph into clusters, via spectral clustering.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Other methods are also available for clustering.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A Markov chain is represented by a matrix whose entries are the transition probabilities between states of a system.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In particular the entries are non-negative, and every row of the matrix sums to one, being the sum of probabilities of transitions from one state to some other state of the system.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The PerronÔÇôFrobenius theorem gives sufficient conditions for a Markov chain to have a unique dominant eigenvalue, which governs the convergence of the system to a steady state.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Eigenvalue problems occur naturally in the vibration analysis of mechanical structures with many degrees of freedom.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigenvalues are the natural frequencies (or '**eigenfrequencies**') of vibration, and the eigenvectors are the shapes of these vibrational modes.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] That is, acceleration is proportional to position (i.e., we expect x to be sinusoidal in time).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In n dimensions, m becomes a mass matrix and k a stiffness matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Admissible solutions are then a linear combination of solutions to the generalized eigenvalue problem $kx=\omega ^{2}mx$ where *¤ë*2 is the eigenvalue and ¤ë is the (imaginary) angular frequency.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The principal vibration modes are different from the principal compliance modes, which are the eigenvectors of k alone.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Furthermore, damped vibration, governed by $m{\ddot {x}}+c{\dot {x}}+kx=0$ leads to a so-called quadratic eigenvalue problem, $\left(\omega ^{2}m+\omega c+k\right)x=0.$ This can be reduced to a generalized eigenvalue problem by algebraic manipulation at the cost of solving a larger system.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The orthogonality properties of the eigenvectors allows decoupling of the differential equations so that the system can be represented as linear summation of the eigenvectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigenvalue problem of complex structures is often solved using finite element analysis, but neatly generalize the solution to scalar-valued vibration problems.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In mechanics, the eigenvectors of the moment of inertia tensor define the principal axes of a rigid body.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The tensor of moment of inertia is a key quantity required to determine the rotation of a rigid body around its center of mass.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In solid mechanics, the stress tensor is symmetric and so can be decomposed into a diagonal tensor with the eigenvalues on the diagonal and eigenvectors as a basis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Because it is diagonal, in this orientation, the stress tensor has no shear components; the components it does have are the principal components.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] However, in the case where one is interested only in the bound state solutions of the Schr├Âdinger equation, one looks for ¤łE within the space of square integrable functions.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Since this space is a Hilbert space with a well-defined scalar product, one can introduce a basis set in which ¤łE and H can be represented as a one-dimensional array (i.e., a vector) and a matrix respectively.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] This allows one to represent the Schr├Âdinger equation in a matrix form.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The braÔÇôket notation is often used in this context.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A vector, which represents a state of the system, in the Hilbert space of square integrable functions is represented by |╬Ę*E*Ôčę.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In this notation, the Schr├Âdinger equation is: $H|\Psi _{E}\rangle =E|\Psi _{E}\rangle$ where |╬Ę*E*Ôčę is an '**eigenstate**' of H, and E represents the eigenvalue.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] H is an observable self-adjoint operator, the infinite-dimensional analog of Hermitian matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] As in the matrix case, in the equation above *H*|╬Ę*E*Ôčę is understood to be the vector obtained by application of the transformation H to |╬Ę*E*Ôčę.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Light, acoustic waves, and microwaves are randomly scattered numerous times when traversing a static disordered system.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Even though multiple scattering repeatedly randomizes the waves, ultimately coherent wave transport through the system is a deterministic process which can be described by a field transmission matrix **t**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigenvectors of the transmission operator **t**ÔÇá**t** form a set of disorder-specific input wavefronts which enable waves to couple into the disordered system's eigenchannels: the independent pathways waves can travel through the system.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigenvalues, ¤ä, of **t**ÔÇá**t** correspond to the intensity transmittance associated with each eigenchannel.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] One of the remarkable properties of the transmission operator of diffusive systems is their bimodal eigenvalue distribution with *¤ä*max = 1 and *¤ä*min = 0.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Furthermore, one of the striking properties of open eigenchannels, beyond the perfect transmittance, is the statistically robust spatial profile of the eigenchannels.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In quantum mechanics, and in particular in atomic and molecular physics, within the HartreeÔÇôFock theory, the atomic and molecular orbitals can be defined by the eigenvectors of the Fock operator.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The corresponding eigenvalues are interpreted as ionization potentials via Koopmans' theorem.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In this case, the term eigenvector is used in a somewhat more general meaning, since the Fock operator is explicitly dependent on the orbitals and their eigenvalues.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Thus, if one wants to underline this aspect, one speaks of nonlinear eigenvalue problems.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Such equations are usually solved by an iteration procedure, called in this case self-consistent field method.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In quantum chemistry, one often represents the HartreeÔÇôFock equation in a non-orthogonal basis set.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] This particular representation is a generalized eigenvalue problem called Roothaan equations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In geology, especially in the study of glacial till, eigenvectors and eigenvalues are used as a method by which a mass of information of a clast's fabric can be summarized in a 3-D space by six numbers.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In the field, a geologist may collect such data for hundreds or thousands of clasts in a soil sample, which can be compared graphically or as a stereographic projection.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Graphically, many geologists use a Tri-Plot (Sneed and Folk) diagram,.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A stereographic projection projects 3-dimensional spaces onto a two-dimensional plane.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] A type of stereographic projection is Wulff Net, which is commonly used in crystallography to create stereograms.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The output for the orientation tensor is in the three orthogonal (perpendicular) axes of space.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The three eigenvectors are ordered **v**1, **v**2, **v**3 by their eigenvalues *E*1 Ôëą *E*2 Ôëą *E*3; **v**1 then is the primary orientation/dip of clast, **v**2 is the secondary and **v**3 is the tertiary, in terms of strength.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The clast orientation is defined as the direction of the eigenvector, on a compass rose of 360┬░.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Dip is measured as the eigenvalue, the modulus of the tensor: this is valued from 0┬░ (no dip) to 90┬░ (vertical).
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The relative values of *E*1, *E*2, and *E*3 are dictated by the nature of the sediment's fabric.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] If *E*1 = *E*2 = *E*3, the fabric is said to be isotropic.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] If *E*1 = *E*2 > *E*3, the fabric is said to be planar.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] If *E*1 > *E*2 > *E*3, the fabric is said to be linear.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The basic reproduction number (*R*0) is a fundamental number in the study of how infectious diseases spread.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] If one infectious person is put into a population of completely susceptible people, then *R*0 is the average number of people that one typical infectious person will infect.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The generation time of an infection is the time, tG, from one person becoming infected to the next person becoming infected.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In a heterogeneous population, the next generation matrix defines how many people in the population will become infected after time tG has passed.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The value *R*0 is then the largest eigenvalue of the next generation matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In image processing, processed images of faces can be seen as vectors whose components are the brightnesses of each pixel.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The dimension of this vector space is the number of pixels.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] The eigenvectors of the covariance matrix associated with a large set of normalized pictures of faces are called **eigenfaces**; this is an example of principal component analysis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] They are very useful for expressing any face image as a linear combination of some of them.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] In the facial recognition branch of biometrics, eigenfaces provide a means of applying data compression to faces for identification purposes.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Research related to eigen vision systems determining hand gestures has also been made.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Similar to this concept, **eigenvoices** represent the general direction of variability in human pronunciations of a particular utterance, such as a word in a language.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] Based on a linear combination of such eigenvoices, a new voice pronunciation of the word can be constructed.
[src:principal-component-analysis/eigenvalues-and-eigenvectors-p02] These concepts have been found useful in automatic speech recognition systems for speaker adaptation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] In machine learning and pattern recognition, a **feature** is an individual measurable property or characteristic of a data set.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Choosing informative, discriminating, and independent features is crucial to producing effective algorithms for pattern recognition, classification, and regression tasks.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Features are usually numeric, but other types such as strings and graphs are used in syntactic pattern recognition, after some pre-processing step such as one-hot encoding.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] The concept of "features" is related to that of explanatory variables used in statistical techniques such as linear regression.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] In feature engineering, two types of features are commonly used: numerical and categorical.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Numerical features are continuous values that can be measured on a scale.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Examples of numerical features include age, height, weight, and income.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Numerical features can be used in machine learning algorithms directly.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Categorical features are discrete values that can be grouped into categories.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Examples of categorical features include gender, color, and zip code.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Categorical features typically need to be converted to numerical features before they can be used in machine learning algorithms.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] This can be done using a variety of techniques, such as one-hot encoding, label encoding, and ordinal encoding.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] The type of feature that is used in feature engineering depends on the specific machine learning algorithm that is being used.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Some machine learning algorithms, such as decision trees, can handle both numerical and categorical features.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Other machine learning algorithms, such as linear regression, can only handle numerical features.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] A numeric feature can be conveniently described by a feature vector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] One way to achieve binary classification is using a linear predictor function (related to the perceptron) with a feature vector as input.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] The method consists of calculating the scalar product between the feature vector and a vector of weights, qualifying those observations whose result exceeds a threshold.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Algorithms for classification from a feature vector include nearest neighbor classification, neural networks, and statistical techniques such as Bayesian approaches.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] In character recognition, features may include histograms counting the number of black pixels along horizontal and vertical directions, number of internal holes, stroke detection and many others.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] In speech recognition, features for recognizing phonemes can include noise ratios, length of sounds, relative power, filter matches, logarithmic Mel-scale spectral vectors and Mel-frequency cepstral coefficients, which represent the frequency characteristics of audio signals.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] In spam detection algorithms, features may include the presence or absence of certain email headers, the email structure, the language, the frequency of specific terms, the grammatical correctness of the text.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] In computer vision, there are a large number of possible features, such as edges and objects.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] In pattern recognition and machine learning, a **feature vector** is an n-dimensional vector of numerical features that represent some object.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Many algorithms in machine learning require a numerical representation of objects, since such representations facilitate processing and statistical analysis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] When representing images, the feature values might correspond to the pixels of an image, while when representing texts the features might be the frequencies of occurrence of textual terms.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Feature vectors are equivalent to the vectors of explanatory variables used in statistical procedures such as linear regression.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Feature vectors are often combined with weights using a dot product in order to construct a linear predictor function that is used to determine a score for making a prediction.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] The vector space associated with these vectors is often called the **feature space**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] In order to reduce the dimensionality of the feature space, a number of dimensionality reduction techniques can be employed.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Higher-level features can be obtained from already available features and added to the feature vector; for example, for the study of diseases the feature 'Age' is useful and is defined as *Age = 'Year of death' minus 'Year of birth'*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] This process is referred to as **feature construction**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Feature construction is the application of a set of constructive operators to a set of existing features resulting in construction of new features.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Feature construction has long been considered a powerful tool for increasing both accuracy and understanding of structure, particularly in high-dimensional problems.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Applications include studies of disease and emotion recognition from speech.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] The initial set of raw features can be redundant and large enough that estimation and optimization is made difficult or ineffective.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Therefore, a preliminary step in many applications of machine learning and pattern recognition consists of selecting a subset of features, or constructing a new and reduced set of features to facilitate learning, and to improve generalization and interpretability.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Extracting or selecting features is a combination of art and science; developing systems to do so is known as feature engineering.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] It requires the experimentation of multiple possibilities and the combination of automated techniques with the intuition and knowledge of the domain expert.
[src:principal-component-analysis/feature-machine-learning] Automating this process is feature learning, where a machine not only uses features for learning, but learns the features itself.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The data are linearly transformed onto a new coordinate system such that the directions (principal components) capturing the largest variation in the data can be easily identified.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The **principal components** of a collection of points in a real coordinate space are a sequence of p unit vectors, where the i -th vector is the direction of a line that best fits the data while being orthogonal to the first $i-1$ vectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Here, a best-fitting line is defined as one that minimizes the average squared perpendicular distance from the points to the line.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] These directions (i.e., principal components) constitute an orthonormal basis in which different individual dimensions of the data are linearly uncorrelated.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Many studies use the first two principal components in order to plot the data in two dimensions and to visually identify clusters of closely related data points.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Principal component analysis has applications in many fields such as population genetics, microbiome studies, and atmospheric science.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] When performing PCA, the first principal component of a set of p variables is the derived variable formed as a linear combination of the original variables that explains the most variance.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The second principal component explains the most variance in what is left once the effect of the first component is removed, and we may proceed through p iterations until all the variance is explained.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is most commonly used when many of the variables are highly correlated with each other and it is desirable to reduce their number to an independent set.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The first principal component can equivalently be defined as a direction that maximizes the variance of the projected data.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The i -th principal component can be taken as a direction orthogonal to the first $i-1$ principal components that maximizes the variance of the projected data.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] For either objective, it can be shown that the principal components are eigenvectors of the data's covariance matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Thus, the principal components are often computed by eigendecomposition of the data covariance matrix or singular value decomposition of the data matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is the simplest of the true eigenvector-based multivariate analyses and is closely related to factor analysis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Factor analysis typically incorporates more domain-specific assumptions about the underlying structure and solves eigenvectors of a slightly different matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is also related to canonical correlation analysis (CCA).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] CCA defines coordinate systems that optimally describe the cross-covariance between two datasets while PCA defines a new orthogonal coordinate system that optimally describes variance in a single dataset.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Robust and L1-norm-based variants of standard PCA have also been proposed.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA was invented in 1901 by Karl Pearson, as an analogue of the principal axis theorem in mechanics; it was later independently developed and named by Harold Hotelling in the 1930s.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA can be thought of as fitting a *p*-dimensional ellipsoid to the data, where each axis of the ellipsoid represents a principal component.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] If some axis of the ellipsoid is small, then the variance along that axis is also small.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] To find the axes of the ellipsoid, we must first center the values of each variable in the dataset on 0 by subtracting the mean of the variable's observed values from each of those values.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] These transformed values are used instead of the original observed values for each of the variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Then, we compute the covariance matrix of the data and calculate the eigenvalues and corresponding eigenvectors of this covariance matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Then we must normalize each of the orthogonal eigenvectors to turn them into unit vectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Once this is done, each of the mutually-orthogonal unit eigenvectors can be interpreted as an axis of the ellipsoid fitted to the data.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] This choice of basis will transform the covariance matrix into a diagonalized form, in which the diagonal elements represent the variance of each axis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The proportion of the variance that each eigenvector represents can be calculated by dividing the eigenvalue corresponding to that eigenvector by the sum of all eigenvalues.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Biplots and scree plots (degree of explained variance) are used to interpret findings of the PCA.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] in such a way that the individual variables $t_{1},\dots ,t_{l}$ of **t** considered over the data set successively inherit the maximum possible variance from **X**, with each coefficient vector **w** constrained to be a unit vector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The quantity to be maximised can be recognised as a Rayleigh quotient.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] A standard result for a positive semidefinite matrix such as **X**T**X** is that the quotient's maximum possible value is the largest eigenvalue of the matrix, which occurs when ***w*** is the corresponding eigenvector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] With **w**(1) found, the first principal component of a data vector **x**(*i*) can then be given as a score *t*1(*i*) = **x**(*i*) Ôőů **w**(1) in the transformed co-ordinates, or as the corresponding vector in the original variables, {**x**(*i*) Ôőů **w**(1)} **w**(1).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] It turns out that this gives the remaining eigenvectors of **X**T**X**, with the maximum values for the quantity in brackets given by their corresponding eigenvalues.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Thus the weight vectors are eigenvectors of **X**T**X**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] where **W** is a *p*-by-*p* matrix of weights whose columns are the eigenvectors of **X**T**X**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The transpose of **W** is sometimes called the whitening or sphering transformation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Columns of **W** multiplied by the square root of corresponding eigenvalues, that is, eigenvectors scaled up by the variances, are called *loadings* in PCA or in Factor analysis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] where the eigenvalue property of **w**(*k*) has been used to move from line 2 to line 3.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] However eigenvectors **w**(*j*) and **w**(*k*) corresponding to eigenvalues of a symmetric matrix are orthogonal (if the eigenvalues are different), or can be orthogonalised (if the vectors happen to share an equal repeated value).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The product in the final line is therefore zero; there is no sample covariance between different principal components over the dataset.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Another way to characterise the principal components transformation is therefore as the transformation to coordinates which diagonalise the empirical sample covariance matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] where **╬Ť** is the diagonal matrix of eigenvalues *╬╗*(*k*) of **X**T**X**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The transformation **P** = **X** **W** maps a data vector **x**(*i*) from an original space of *x* variables to a new space of *p* variables which are uncorrelated over the dataset.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] These norms are used to transform the original space of variables *x, y* to a new space of uncorrelated variables *p, q* (given *Yc* with same meaning), such that $p_{i}={\frac {X_{i}}{X_{c}}},\quad q_{i}={\frac {Y_{i}}{Y_{c}}}$ ; and the new variables are linearly related as: $q=\alpha p$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Such dimensionality reduction can be a very useful step for visualising and processing high-dimensional datasets, while still retaining as much of the variance in the dataset as possible.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Similarly, in regression analysis, the larger the number of explanatory variables allowed, the greater is the chance of overfitting the model, producing conclusions that fail to generalise to other datasets.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] One approach, especially when there are strong correlations between different possible explanatory variables, is to reduce them to a few principal components and then run the regression against them, a method called principal component regression.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Dimensionality reduction may also be appropriate when the variables in a dataset are noisy.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] However, with more of the total variance concentrated in the first few principal components compared to the same noise variance, the proportionate effect of the noise is lessÔÇöthe first few components achieve a higher signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA thus can have the effect of concentrating much of the signal into the first few principal components, which can usefully be captured by dimensionality reduction; while the later principal components may be dominated by noise, and so disposed of without great loss.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] If the dataset is not too large, the significance of the principal components can be tested using parametric bootstrap, as an aid in determining how many principal components to retain.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] where **$\mathbf {\hat {\Sigma }}$** is the square diagonal matrix with the singular values of **X**and the excess zeros chopped off that satisfies**$\mathbf {{\hat {\Sigma }}^{2}} =\mathbf {\Sigma } ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {\Sigma }$**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Comparison with the eigenvector factorization of **X**T**X** establishes that the right singular vectors **W** of **X** are equivalent to the eigenvectors of **X**T**X**, while the singular values *¤â*(*k*) of **$\mathbf {X}$** are equal to the square-root of the eigenvalues *╬╗*(*k*) of **X**T**X**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] so each column of **T** is given by one of the left singular vectors of **X** multiplied by the corresponding singular value.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] This form is also the polar decomposition of **T**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Efficient algorithms exist to calculate the SVD of **X** without having to form the matrix **X**T**X**, so computing the SVD is now the standard way to calculate a principal components analysis from a data matrix, unless only a handful of components are required.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The singular values (in **╬ú**) are the square roots of the eigenvalues of the matrix **X**T**X**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Each eigenvalue is proportional to the portion of the "variance" (more correctly of the sum of the squared distances of the points from their multidimensional mean) that is associated with each eigenvector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The sum of all the eigenvalues is equal to the sum of the squared distances of the points from their multidimensional mean.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA essentially rotates the set of points around their mean in order to align with the principal components.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] This moves as much of the variance as possible (using an orthogonal transformation) into the first few dimensions.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The values in the remaining dimensions, therefore, tend to be small and may be dropped with minimal loss of information (see below).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is often used in this manner for dimensionality reduction.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA has the distinction of being the optimal orthogonal transformation for keeping the subspace that has largest "variance" (as defined above).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] This advantage, however, comes at the price of greater computational requirements if compared, for example, and when applicable, to the discrete cosine transform, and in particular to the DCT-II which is simply known as the "DCT".
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Nonlinear dimensionality reduction techniques tend to be more computationally demanding than PCA.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is sensitive to the scaling of the variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Mathematically this sensitivity comes from the way a rescaling changes the sampleÔÇĹcovariance matrix that PCA diagonalises.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Because the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of $\Sigma ^{(\alpha )}$ are those of $\Sigma$ scaled by D , the principal axes rotate toward any column whose variance has been inflated, exactly as the 2ÔÇĹD example below illustrates.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] If we have just two variables and they have the same sample variance and are completely correlated, then the PCA will entail a rotation by 45┬░ and the "weights" (they are the cosines of rotation) for the two variables with respect to the principal component will be equal.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] But if we multiply all values of the first variable by 100, then the first principal component will be almost the same as that variable, with a small contribution from the other variable, whereas the second component will be almost aligned with the second original variable.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] This means that whenever the different variables have different units (like temperature and mass), PCA is a somewhat arbitrary method of analysis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] (Different results would be obtained if one used Fahrenheit rather than Celsius for example.) Pearson's original paper was entitled "On Lines and Planes of Closest Fit to Systems of Points in Space" ÔÇô "in space" implies physical Euclidean space where such concerns do not arise.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] One way of making the PCA less arbitrary is to use variables scaled so as to have unit variance, by standardizing the data and hence use the autocorrelation matrix instead of the autocovariance matrix as a basis for PCA.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] However, this compresses (or expands) the fluctuations in all dimensions of the signal space to unit variance.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Classical PCA assumes the cloud of points has already been translated so its centroid is at the origin.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] where $\mathbf {Z}$ is the centered matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The rankÔÇĹone term $n\,{\boldsymbol {\mu }}{\boldsymbol {\mu }}^{\mathsf {T}}$ often dominates, forcing the leading eigenvector to point almost exactly toward the mean and obliterating any structure in the centred part $\mathbf {Z}$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] After mean subtraction that term vanishes and the principal axes align with the true directions of maximal variance.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Mean-centering is unnecessary if performing a principal components analysis on a correlation matrix, as the data are already centered after calculating correlations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Correlations are derived from the cross-product of two standard scores (Z-scores) or statistical moments (hence the name: *Pearson Product-Moment Correlation*).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Also see the article by Kromrey & Foster-Johnson (1998) on *"Mean-centering in Moderated Regression: Much Ado About Nothing"*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Since covariances are correlations of normalized variables (Z- or standard-scores) a PCA based on the correlation matrix of **X** is equal to a PCA based on the covariance matrix of **Z**, the standardized version of **X**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is a popular primary technique in pattern recognition.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] It is not, however, optimized for class separability.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] However, it has been used to quantify the distance between two or more classes by calculating center of mass for each class in principal component space and reporting Euclidean distance between center of mass of two or more classes.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The linear discriminant analysis is an alternative which is optimized for class separability.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The statistical implication of this property is that the last few PCs are not simply unstructured left-overs after removing the important PCs.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Because these last PCs have variances as small as possible they are useful in their own right.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] They can help to detect unsuspected near-constant linear relationships between the elements of x, and they may also be useful in regression, in selecting a subset of variables from x, and in outlier detection.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] As noted above, the results of PCA depend on the scaling of the variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] This can be cured by scaling each feature by its standard deviation, so that one ends up with dimensionless features with unital variance.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The applicability of PCA as described above is limited by certain (tacit) assumptions made in its derivation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] In particular, PCA can capture linear correlations between the features but fails when this assumption is violated (see Figure 6a in the reference).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] In some cases, coordinate transformations can restore the linearity assumption and PCA can then be applied (see kernel PCA).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Another limitation is the mean-removal process before constructing the covariance matrix for PCA.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] In fields such as astronomy, all the signals are non-negative, and the mean-removal process will force the mean of some astrophysical exposures to be zero, which consequently creates unphysical negative fluxes, and forward modeling has to be performed to recover the true magnitude of the signals.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] As an alternative method, non-negative matrix factorization focusing only on the non-negative elements in the matrices is well-suited for astrophysical observations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] See more at the relation between PCA and non-negative matrix factorization.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is at a disadvantage if the data has not been standardized before applying the algorithm to it.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA transforms the original data into data that is relevant to the principal components of that data, which means that the new data variables cannot be interpreted in the same ways that the originals were.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] They are linear interpretations of the original variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Also, if PCA is not performed properly, there is a high likelihood of information loss.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] If a dataset has a pattern hidden inside it that is nonlinear, then PCA can actually steer the analysis in the complete opposite direction of progress.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Researchers at Kansas State University discovered that the sampling error in their experiments impacted the bias of PCA results.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] "If the number of subjects or blocks is smaller than 30, and/or the researcher is interested in PC's beyond the first, it may be better to first correct for the serial correlation, before PCA is conducted".
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The researchers at Kansas State also found that PCA could be "seriously biased if the autocorrelation structure of the data are not correctly handled".
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Dimensionality reduction results in a loss of information, in general.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA-based dimensionality reduction tends to minimize that information loss, under certain signal and noise models.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] that is, that the data vector $\mathbf {x}$ is the sum of the desired information-bearing signal $\mathbf {s}$ and a noise signal $\mathbf {n}$ one can show that PCA can be optimal for dimensionality reduction, from an information-theoretic point-of-view.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The optimality of PCA is also preserved if the noise $\mathbf {n}$ is iid and at least more Gaussian (in terms of the KullbackÔÇôLeibler divergence) than the information-bearing signal $\mathbf {s}$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] In general, even if the above signal model holds, PCA loses its information-theoretic optimality as soon as the noise $\mathbf {n}$ becomes dependent.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The following is a detailed description of PCA using the covariance method as opposed to the correlation method.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The goal is to transform a given data set **X** of dimension *p* to an alternative data set **Y** of smaller dimension *L*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] **Calculate the deviations from the mean** Mean subtraction is an integral part of the solution towards finding a principal component basis that minimizes the mean square error of approximating the data.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Hence we proceed by centering the data as follows: In some applications, each variable (column of **B**) may also be scaled to have a variance equal to 1 (see Z-score).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] This step affects the calculated principal components, but makes them independent of the units used to measure the different variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] **Project the data onto the new basis** That is, the first column of $\mathbf {T}$ is the projection of the data points onto the first principal component, the second column is the projection onto the second principal component, etc.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Let **X** be a *d*-dimensional random vector expressed as column vector.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Without loss of generality, assume **X** has zero mean.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] We want to find $(\ast )$ a *d* ├Ś *d* orthonormal transformation matrix **P** so that **PX** has a diagonal covariance matrix (that is, **PX** is a random vector with all its distinct components pairwise uncorrelated).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Hence $(\ast )$ holds if and only if $\operatorname {cov} (X)$ were diagonalisable by P .
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] This is very constructive, as cov(**X**) is guaranteed to be a non-negative definite matrix and thus is guaranteed to be diagonalisable by some unitary matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] In practical implementations, especially with high dimensional data (large p), the naive covariance method is rarely used because it is not efficient due to high computational and memory costs of explicitly determining the covariance matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The covariance-free approach avoids the *np*2 operations of explicitly calculating and storing the covariance matrix **XTX**, instead utilizing one of matrix-free methods, for example, based on the function evaluating the product **XT(X r)** at the cost of 2*np* operations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] One way to compute the first principal component efficiently is shown in the following pseudo-code, for a data matrix **X** with zero mean, without ever computing its covariance matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] This power iteration algorithm simply calculates the vector **XT(X r)**, normalizes, and places the result back in **r**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The eigenvalue is approximated by **rT (XTX) r**, which is the Rayleigh quotient on the unit vector **r** for the covariance matrix **XTX**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] If the largest singular value is well separated from the next largest one, the vector **r** gets close to the first principal component of **X** within the number of iterations c, which is small relative to p, at the total cost *2cnp*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The power iteration convergence can be accelerated without noticeably sacrificing the small cost per iteration using more advanced matrix-free methods, such as the Lanczos algorithm or the Locally Optimal Block Preconditioned Conjugate Gradient (LOBPCG) method.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Subsequent principal components can be computed one-by-one via deflation or simultaneously as a block.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] In the former approach, imprecisions in already computed approximate principal components additively affect the accuracy of the subsequently computed principal components, thus increasing the error with every new computation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The latter approach in the block power method replaces single-vectors **r** and **s** with block-vectors, matrices **R** and **S**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Every column of **R** approximates one of the leading principal components, while all columns are iterated simultaneously.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The main calculation is evaluation of the product **XT(X R)**.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Implemented, for example, in LOBPCG, efficient blocking eliminates the accumulation of the errors, allows using high-level BLAS matrix-matrix product functions, and typically leads to faster convergence, compared to the single-vector one-by-one technique.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The matrix deflation by subtraction is performed by subtracting the outer product, **t**1**r**1T from **X** leaving the deflated residual matrix used to calculate the subsequent leading PCs.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] For large data matrices, or matrices that have a high degree of column collinearity, NIPALS suffers from loss of orthogonality of PCs due to machine precision round-off errors accumulated in each iteration and matrix deflation by subtraction.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] A GramÔÇôSchmidt re-orthogonalization algorithm is applied to both the scores and the loadings at each iteration step to eliminate this loss of orthogonality.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] In an "online" or "streaming" situation with data arriving piece by piece rather than being stored in a single batch, it is useful to make an estimate of the PCA projection that can be updated sequentially.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] This can be done efficiently, but requires different algorithms.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] In exploratory data analysis, qualitative (categorical) variables not used to construct the model can be projected onto the principal component axes as supplementary elements.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] The use of supplementary qualitative variables was a defining feature of the French school of data analysis developed in the 1960s and 70s.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p01] Based upon the work of Ludovic Lebart, the method is available in the R environment through packages such as FactoMineR.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The earliest application of factor analysis was in locating and measuring components of human intelligence.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The pioneering statistical psychologist Spearman actually developed factor analysis in 1904 for his two-factor theory of intelligence, adding a formal technique to the science of psychometrics.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In 1924 Thurstone looked for 56 factors of intelligence, developing the notion of Mental Age.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Standard IQ tests today are based on this early work.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In 1949, Shevky and Williams introduced the theory of **factorial ecology**, which dominated studies of residential differentiation from the 1950s to the 1970s.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Neighbourhoods in a city were recognizable or could be distinguished from one another by various characteristics which could be reduced to three by factor analysis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] These were known as 'social rank' (an index of occupational status), 'familism' or family size, and 'ethnicity'; Cluster analysis could then be applied to divide the city into clusters or precincts according to values of the three key factor variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] An extensive literature developed around factorial ecology in urban geography, but the approach went out of fashion after 1980 as being methodologically primitive and having little place in postmodern geographical paradigms.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] One of the problems with factor analysis has always been finding convincing names for the various artificial factors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In 2000, Flood revived the factorial ecology approach to show that principal components analysis actually gave meaningful answers directly, without resorting to factor rotation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The principal components were actually dual variables or shadow prices of 'forces' pushing people together or apart in cities.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The first component was 'accessibility', the classic trade-off between demand for travel and demand for space, around which classical urban economics is based.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The next two components were 'disadvantage', which keeps people of similar status in separate neighbourhoods (mediated by planning), and ethnicity, where people of similar ethnic backgrounds try to co-locate.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] About the same time, the Australian Bureau of Statistics defined distinct indexes of advantage and disadvantage taking the first principal component of sets of key variables that were thought to be important.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] These SEIFA indexes are regularly published for various jurisdictions, and are used frequently in spatial analysis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA can be used as a formal method for the development of indexes.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] As an alternative confirmatory composite analysis has been proposed to develop and assess indexes.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The City Development Index was developed by PCA from about 200 indicators of city outcomes in a 1996 survey of 254 global cities.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The first principal component was subject to iterative regression, adding the original variables singly until about 90% of its variation was accounted for.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The index ultimately used about 15 indicators but was a good predictor of many more variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Its comparative value agreed very well with a subjective assessment of the condition of each city.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The coefficients on items of infrastructure were roughly proportional to the average costs of providing the underlying services, suggesting the Index was actually a measure of effective physical and social investment in the city.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The country-level Human Development Index (HDI) from UNDP, which has been published since 1990 and is very extensively used in development studies, has very similar coefficients on similar indicators, strongly suggesting it was originally constructed using PCA.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In 1978 Cavalli-Sforza and others pioneered the use of principal components analysis (PCA) to summarise data on variation in human gene frequencies across regions.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The components showed distinctive patterns, including gradients and sinusoidal waves.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] They interpreted these patterns as resulting from specific ancient migration events.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Since then, PCA has been ubiquitous in population genetics, with thousands of papers using PCA as a display mechanism.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Genetics varies largely according to proximity, so the first two principal components actually show spatial distribution and may be used to map the relative geographical location of different population groups, thereby showing individuals who have wandered from their original locations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA in genetics has been technically controversial, in that the technique has been performed on discrete non-normal variables and often on binary allele markers.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The lack of any measures of standard error in PCA are also an impediment to more consistent usage.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In August 2022, the molecular biologist Eran Elhaik published a theoretical paper in Scientific Reports analyzing 12 PCA applications.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] He concluded that it was easy to manipulate the method, which, in his view, generated results that were 'erroneous, contradictory, and absurd.' Specifically, he argued, the results achieved in population genetics were characterized by cherry-picking and circular reasoning.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Market research has been an extensive user of PCA.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] It is used to develop customer satisfaction or customer loyalty scores for products, and with clustering, to develop market segments that may be targeted with advertising campaigns, in much the same way as factorial ecology will locate geographical areas with similar characteristics.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA rapidly transforms large amounts of data into smaller, easier-to-digest variables that can be more rapidly and readily analyzed.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In any consumer questionnaire, there are series of questions designed to elicit consumer attitudes, and principal components seek out latent variables underlying these attitudes.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] For example, the Oxford Internet Survey in 2013 asked 2000 people about their attitudes and beliefs, and from these analysts extracted four principal component dimensions, which they identified as 'escape', 'social networking', 'efficiency', and 'problem creating'.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Another example from Joe Flood in 2008 extracted an attitudinal index toward housing from 28 attitude questions in a national survey of 2697 households in Australia.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The first principal component represented a general attitude toward property and home ownership.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The index, or the attitude questions it embodied, could be fed into a General Linear Model of tenure choice.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The strongest determinant of private renting by far was the attitude index, rather than income, marital status or household type.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In quantitative finance, PCA is used in financial risk management, and has been applied to other problems such as portfolio optimization.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA is commonly used in problems involving fixed income securities and portfolios, and interest rate derivatives.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Valuations here depend on the entire yield curve, comprising numerous highly correlated instruments, and PCA is used to define a set of components or factors that explain rate movements, thereby facilitating the modelling.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] One common risk management application is to calculating value at risk, VaR, applying PCA to the Monte Carlo simulation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Here, for each simulation-sample, the components are stressed, and rates, and in turn option values, are then reconstructed; with VaR calculated, finally, over the entire run.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA is also used in hedging exposure to interest rate risk, given partial durations and other sensitivities.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Under both, the first three, typically, principal components of the system are of interest (representing "shift", "twist", and "curvature").
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] These principal components are derived from an eigen-decomposition of the covariance matrix of yield at predefined maturities; and where the variance of each component is its eigenvalue (and as the components are orthogonal, no correlation need be incorporated in subsequent modelling).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] For equity, an optimal portfolio is one where the expected return is maximized for a given level of risk, or alternatively, where risk is minimized for a given return; see Markowitz model for discussion.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Thus, one approach is to reduce portfolio risk, where allocation strategies are applied to the "principal portfolios" instead of the underlying stocks.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] A second approach is to enhance portfolio return, using the principal components to select companies' stocks with upside potential.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA has also been used to understand relationships between international equity markets, and within markets between groups of companies in industries or sectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA may also be applied to stress testing, essentially an analysis of a bank's ability to endure a hypothetical adverse economic scenario.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] A variant of principal components analysis is used in neuroscience to identify the specific properties of a stimulus that increases a neuron's probability of generating an action potential.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] This technique is known as spike-triggered covariance analysis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In a typical application an experimenter presents a white noise process as a stimulus (usually either as a sensory input to a test subject, or as a current injected directly into the neuron) and records a train of action potentials, or spikes, produced by the neuron as a result.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Presumably, certain features of the stimulus make the neuron more likely to spike.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In order to extract these features, the experimenter calculates the covariance matrix of the *spike-triggered ensemble*, the set of all stimuli (defined and discretized over a finite time window, typically on the order of 100 ms) that immediately preceded a spike.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Specifically, the eigenvectors with the largest positive eigenvalues correspond to the directions along which the variance of the spike-triggered ensemble showed the largest positive change compared to the variance of the prior.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Since these were the directions in which varying the stimulus led to a spike, they are often good approximations of the sought after relevant stimulus features.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In neuroscience, PCA is also used to discern the identity of a neuron from the shape of its action potential.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Spike sorting is an important procedure because extracellular recording techniques often pick up signals from more than one neuron.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In spike sorting, one first uses PCA to reduce the dimensionality of the space of action potential waveforms, and then performs clustering analysis to associate specific action potentials with individual neurons.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA as a dimension reduction technique is particularly suited to detect coordinated activities of large neuronal ensembles.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] It has been used in determining collective variables, that is, order parameters, during phase transitions in the brain.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Correspondence analysis (CA) was developed by Jean-Paul Benz├ęcri and is conceptually similar to PCA, but scales the data (which should be non-negative) so that rows and columns are treated equivalently.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] It is traditionally applied to contingency tables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] CA decomposes the chi-squared statistic associated to this table into orthogonal factors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Because CA is a descriptive technique, it can be applied to tables for which the chi-squared statistic is appropriate or not.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Several variants of CA are available including detrended correspondence analysis and canonical correspondence analysis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] One special extension is multiple correspondence analysis, which may be seen as the counterpart of principal component analysis for categorical data.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Principal component analysis creates variables that are linear combinations of the original variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The new variables have the property that the variables are all orthogonal.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The PCA transformation can be helpful as a pre-processing step before clustering.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA is a variance-focused approach seeking to reproduce the total variable variance, in which components reflect both common and unique variance of the variable.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA is generally preferred for purposes of data reduction (that is, translating variable space into optimal factor space) but not when the goal is to detect the latent construct or factors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Factor analysis is similar to principal component analysis, in that factor analysis also involves linear combinations of variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Different from PCA, factor analysis is a correlation-focused approach seeking to reproduce the inter-correlations among variables, in which the factors "represent the common variance of variables, excluding unique variance".
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In terms of the correlation matrix, this corresponds with focusing on explaining the off-diagonal terms (that is, shared co-variance), while PCA focuses on explaining the terms that sit on the diagonal.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] However, as a side result, when trying to reproduce the on-diagonal terms, PCA also tends to fit relatively well the off-diagonal correlations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Results given by PCA and factor analysis are very similar in most situations, but this is not always the case, and there are some problems where the results are significantly different.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Factor analysis is generally used when the research purpose is detecting data structure (that is, latent constructs or factors) or causal modeling.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] If the factor model is incorrectly formulated or the assumptions are not met, then factor analysis will give erroneous results.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] It has been asserted that the relaxed solution of *k*-means clustering, specified by the cluster indicators, is given by the principal components, and the PCA subspace spanned by the principal directions is identical to the cluster centroid subspace.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] However, that PCA is a useful relaxation of *k*-means clustering was not a new result, and it is straightforward to uncover counterexamples to the statement that the cluster centroid subspace is spanned by the principal directions.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Non-negative matrix factorization (NMF) is a dimension reduction method where only non-negative elements in the matrices are used, which is therefore a promising method in astronomy, in the sense that astrophysical signals are non-negative.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The PCA components are orthogonal to each other, while the NMF components are all non-negative and therefore constructs a non-orthogonal basis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In PCA, the contribution of each component is ranked based on the magnitude of its corresponding eigenvalue, which is equivalent to the fractional residual variance (FRV) in analyzing empirical data.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] For NMF, its components are ranked based only on the empirical FRV curves.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The FRV curves for NMF is decreasing continuously when the NMF components are constructed sequentially, indicating the continuous capturing of quasi-static noise; then converge to higher levels than PCA, indicating the less over-fitting property of NMF.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] It is often difficult to interpret the principal components when the data include many variables of various origins, or when some variables are qualitative.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] This leads the PCA user to a delicate elimination of several variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] If observations or variables have an excessive impact on the direction of the axes, they should be removed and then projected as supplementary elements.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In addition, it is necessary to avoid interpreting the proximities between the points close to the center of the factorial plane.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The iconography of correlations, on the contrary, which is not a projection on a system of axes, does not have these drawbacks.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] We can therefore keep all the variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The principle of the diagram is to underline the "remarkable" correlations of the correlation matrix, by a solid line (positive correlation) or dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] A strong correlation is not "remarkable" if it is not direct, but caused by the effect of a third variable.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Conversely, weak correlations can be "remarkable".
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] For example, if a variable Y depends on several independent variables, the correlations of Y with each of them are weak and yet "remarkable".
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] A particular disadvantage of PCA is that the principal components are usually linear combinations of all input variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Sparse PCA overcomes this disadvantage by finding linear combinations that contain just a few input variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] It extends the classic method of principal component analysis (PCA) for the reduction of dimensionality of data by adding sparsity constraint on the input variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The methodological and theoretical developments of Sparse PCA as well as its applications in scientific studies were recently reviewed in a survey paper.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Most of the modern methods for nonlinear dimensionality reduction find their theoretical and algorithmic roots in PCA or K-means.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Pearson's original idea was to take a straight line (or plane) which will be "the best fit" to a set of data points.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Trevor Hastie expanded on this concept by proposing **Principal curves** as the natural extension for the geometric interpretation of PCA, which explicitly constructs a manifold for data approximation followed by projecting the points onto it.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] See also the elastic map algorithm and principal geodesic analysis.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Another popular generalization is kernel PCA, which corresponds to PCA performed in a reproducing kernel Hilbert space associated with a positive definite kernel.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] In multilinear subspace learning, PCA is generalized to multilinear PCA (MPCA) that extracts features directly from tensor representations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] MPCA is solved by performing PCA in each mode of the tensor iteratively.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] MPCA has been applied to face recognition, gait recognition, etc.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] MPCA is further extended to uncorrelated MPCA, non-negative MPCA and robust MPCA.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] While PCA finds the mathematically optimal method (as in minimizing the squared error), it is still sensitive to outliers in the data that produce large errors, something that the method tries to avoid in the first place.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] It is therefore common practice to remove outliers before computing PCA.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] However, in some contexts, outliers can be difficult to identify.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] For example, in data mining algorithms like correlation clustering, the assignment of points to clusters and outliers is not known beforehand.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] A recently proposed generalization of PCA based on a weighted PCA increases robustness by assigning different weights to data objects based on their estimated relevancy.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Outlier-resistant variants of PCA have also been proposed, based on L1-norm formulations (L1-PCA).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Robust principal component analysis (RPCA) via decomposition in low-rank and sparse matrices is a modification of PCA that works well with respect to grossly corrupted observations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Independent component analysis (ICA) is directed to similar problems as principal component analysis, but finds additively separable components rather than successive approximations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Given a matrix E , it tries to decompose it into two matrices such that $E=AP$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] A key difference from techniques such as PCA and ICA is that some of the entries of A are constrained to be 0.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Each column of A must have at least $L-1$ zeroes where L is the number of columns of A (or alternatively the number of rows of P ).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The justification for this criterion is that if a node is removed from the regulatory layer along with all the output nodes connected to it, the result must still be characterized by a connectivity matrix with full column rank.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] then the decomposition is unique up to multiplication by a scalar.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Discriminant analysis of principal components (DAPC) is a multivariate method used to identify and describe clusters of genetically related individuals.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Genetic variation is partitioned into two components: variation between groups and within groups, and it maximizes the former.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Linear discriminants are linear combinations of alleles which best separate the clusters.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Alleles that most contribute to this discrimination are therefore those that are the most markedly different across groups.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] A DAPC can be realized on R using the package Adegenet.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Directional component analysis (DCA) is a method used in the atmospheric sciences for analysing multivariate datasets.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Like PCA, it allows for dimension reduction, improved visualization and improved interpretability of large data-sets.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Also like PCA, it is based on a covariance matrix derived from the input dataset.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The difference between PCA and DCA is that DCA additionally requires the input of a vector direction, referred to as the impact.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] Whereas PCA maximises explained variance, DCA maximises probability density given impact.
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] The motivation for DCA is to find components of a multivariate dataset that are both likely (measured using probability density) and important (measured using the impact).
[src:principal-component-analysis/principal-component-analysis-p02] DCA has been used to find the most likely and most serious heat-wave patterns in weather prediction ensembles , and the most likely and most impactful changes in rainfall due to climate change .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In linear algebra, the **singular value decomposition** (**SVD**) is a factorization of a real or complex matrix into a rotation, followed by a scaling, followed by another rotation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It generalizes the eigendecomposition of a square normal matrix with an orthonormal eigenbasis to any Ôüá $m\times n$ Ôüá matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It is related to the polar decomposition.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Such decompositions always exist for any complex matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá is real, then Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {V}$ Ôüá can be guaranteed to be real orthogonal matrices; in such contexts, the SVD is often denoted Ôüá $\mathbf {U\Sigma V} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The diagonal entries $\sigma _{i}=\mathbf {\Sigma } _{ii}$ of $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ are uniquely determined by Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá up to reordering and are known as the singular values of Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The number of non-zero singular values is equal to the rank of Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The columns of Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and the columns of Ôüá $\mathbf {V}$ Ôüá are called left-singular vectors and right-singular vectors of Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá, respectively.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] However, it is always possible to choose the decomposition such that the singular values $\mathbf {\Sigma } _{ii}$ are in descending order.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In this case, $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ (but not Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {V}$ Ôüá) is uniquely determined by Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Mathematical applications of the SVD include computing the pseudoinverse, matrix approximation, and determining the rank, range, and null space of a matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD is also extremely useful in many areas of science, engineering, and statistics, such as signal processing, least squares fitting of data, and process control.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In the special case when Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá is an Ôüá $m\times m$ Ôüá real square matrix, the matrices Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá can be chosen to be real Ôüá $m\times m$ Ôüá matrices too.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In that case, "unitary" is the same as "orthogonal".
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In particular, if Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá has a positive determinant, then Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá can be chosen to be both rotations with reflections, or both rotations without reflections.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If the determinant is negative, exactly one of them will have a reflection.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If the determinant is zero, each can be independently chosen to be of either type.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If the matrix Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá is real but not square, namely Ôüá $m\times n$ Ôüá with Ôüá $m\neq n$ Ôüá, it can be interpreted as a linear transformation from Ôüá $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ Ôüá to Ôüá $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] As shown in the figure, the singular values can be interpreted as the magnitude of the semiaxes of an ellipse in 2D.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This concept can be generalized to Ôüá n Ôüá-dimensional Euclidean space, with the singular values of any Ôüá $n\times n$ Ôüá square matrix being viewed as the magnitude of the semiaxis of an Ôüá n Ôüá-dimensional ellipsoid.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Similarly, the singular values of any Ôüá $m\times n$ Ôüá matrix can be viewed as the magnitude of the semiaxis of an Ôüá n Ôüá-dimensional ellipsoid in Ôüá m Ôüá-dimensional space, for example as an ellipse in a (tilted) 2D plane in a 3D space.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Singular values encode magnitude of the semiaxis, while singular vectors encode direction.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Since Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá are unitary, the columns of each of them form a set of orthonormal vectors, which can be regarded as basis vectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The matrix Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá maps the basis vector Ôüá $\mathbf {V} _{i}$ Ôüá to the stretched unit vector Ôüá $\sigma _{i}\mathbf {U} _{i}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] By the definition of a unitary matrix, the same is true for their conjugate transposes Ôüá $\mathbf {U} ^{*}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {V}$ Ôüá, except the geometric interpretation of the singular values as stretches is lost.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] When Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá is a positive-semidefinite Hermitian matrix, Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {V}$ Ôüá are both equal to the unitary matrix used to diagonalize Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] However, when Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá is not positive-semidefinite and Hermitian but still diagonalizable, its eigendecomposition and singular value decomposition are distinct.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] With respect to these bases, the map Ôüá T Ôüá is therefore represented by a diagonal matrix with non-negative real diagonal entries.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] To get a more visual flavor of singular values and SVD factorization ÔÇô at least when working on real vector spaces ÔÇô consider the sphere Ôüá S Ôüá of radius one in Ôüá $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The linear map Ôüá T Ôüá maps this sphere onto an ellipsoid in Ôüá $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Non-zero singular values are simply the lengths of the semi-axes of this ellipsoid.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] These directions happen to be mutually orthogonal.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Apply first an isometry Ôüá $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá sending these directions to the coordinate axes of Ôüá $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] On a second move, apply an endomorphism Ôüá $\mathbf {D}$ Ôüá diagonalized along the coordinate axes and stretching or shrinking in each direction, using the semi-axis lengths of Ôüá $T(S)$ Ôüá as scaling coefficients.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The composition Ôüá $\mathbf {D} \circ \mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá then sends the unit-sphere onto an ellipsoid isometric to Ôüá $T(S)$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] To define the third and last move, apply an isometry Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá to this ellipsoid to obtain Ôüá $T(S)$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] As can be easily checked, the composition Ôüá $\mathbf {U} \circ \mathbf {D} \circ \mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá coincides with Ôüá T Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The singular values of Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá are the diagonal entries of Ôüá $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ Ôüá: ${\color {PineGreen}3},{\color {BrickRed}{\sqrt {5}}},{\color {BlueViolet}2},{\color {CadetBlue}0}$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The corresponding left- and right-singular vectors are the columns of Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and rows of Ôüá $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá, respectively.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The matrix Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá has rank Ôüá 3 Ôüá, so there are only three non-zero singular values.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Likewise for the last column of Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The vectors Ôüá $\mathbf {u}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {v}$ Ôüá are called **left-singular** and **right-singular vectors** for Ôüá $\sigma$ Ôüá, respectively.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In any singular value decomposition $\mathbf {M} =\mathbf {U} \mathbf {\Sigma } \mathbf {V} ^{*},$ the diagonal entries of Ôüá $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ Ôüá are equal to the singular values of Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The first Ôüá $p=\min\{m,n\}$ Ôüá columns of Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {V}$ Ôüá are, respectively, left- and right-singular vectors for the corresponding singular values.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A singular value for which we can find two left- (or right-) singular vectors that are linearly independent is called *degenerate*.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If Ôüá $\mathbf {u} _{1}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {u} _{2}$ Ôüá are two left-singular vectors which both correspond to the singular value Ôüá $\sigma$ Ôüá, then any normalized linear combination of the two vectors is also a left-singular vector corresponding to the singular value Ôüá $\sigma$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The similar statement is true for right-singular vectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The numbers of independent left- and right-singular vectors coincide, and these singular vectors appear in the same columns of Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {V}$ Ôüá: those corresponding to the diagonal elements of Ôüá $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ Ôüá with the same value Ôüá $\sigma$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] As an exception, the left- and right-singular vectors of singular value Ôüá 0 Ôüá comprise all unit vectors in the cokernel and kernel, respectively, of Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] By the rankÔÇônullity theorem, these subspaces cannot have the same dimension if Ôüá $m\neq n$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Even when all singular values are non-zero, if Ôüá $m>n$ Ôüá, then the cokernel is non-trivial, in which case Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá is padded with Ôüá $m-n$ Ôüá orthogonal [orthonormal?] vectors from the cokernel.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Conversely, if Ôüá $m<n$ Ôüá, then Ôüá $\mathbf {V}$ Ôüá is padded by Ôüá $n-m$ Ôüá orthogonal [orthonormal?] vectors from the kernel.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] However, if the singular value Ôüá 0 Ôüá exists, the extra columns of Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá or Ôüá $\mathbf {V}$ Ôüá already appear as left- or right-singular vectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Non-degenerate singular values always have unique left- and right-singular vectors, up to multiplication by a (unit) phase factor Ôüá $e^{i\varphi }$ Ôüá (for the real case, up to a sign).
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In general, the SVD is unique up to arbitrary unitary transformations applied uniformly to the column vectors of both Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {V}$ Ôüá of Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The singular value decomposition is very general in the sense that it can be applied to any Ôüá $m\times n$ Ôüá matrix, whereas eigenvalue decomposition can only be applied to square diagonalizable matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Nevertheless, the two decompositions are related.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The right-hand sides of these relations describe the eigenvalue decompositions of the left-hand sides.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] When Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá is positive semi-definite, Ôüá $\sigma _{i}$ Ôüá will be non-negative real numbers so that the decomposition Ôüá $\mathbf {M} =\mathbf {U} \mathbf {D} \mathbf {U} ^{*}$ Ôüá is also a singular value decomposition.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The singular value decomposition can be used for computing the pseudoinverse of a matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The pseudoinverse is one way to solve linear least squares problems.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A set of homogeneous linear equations can be written as Ôüá $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {x} =\mathbf {0}$ Ôüá for a matrix Ôüá $\mathbf {A}$ Ôüá, vector Ôüá $\mathbf {x}$ Ôüá, and zero vector Ôüá $\mathbf {0}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A typical situation is that Ôüá $\mathbf {A}$ Ôüá is known and a non-zero Ôüá $\mathbf {x}$ Ôüá is to be determined which satisfies the equation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Such an Ôüá $\mathbf {x}$ Ôüá belongs to Ôüá $\mathbf {A}$ Ôüá's null space and is sometimes called a (right) null vector of Ôüá $\mathbf {A} .$ Ôüá The vector Ôüá $\mathbf {x}$ Ôüá can be characterized as a right-singular vector corresponding to a singular value of Ôüá $\mathbf {A}$ Ôüá that is zero.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This observation means that if Ôüá $\mathbf {A}$ Ôüá is a square matrix and has no vanishing singular value, the equation has no non-zero Ôüá $\mathbf {x}$ Ôüá as a solution.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It also means that if there are several vanishing singular values, any linear combination of the corresponding right-singular vectors is a valid solution.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A total least squares problem seeks the vector Ôüá $\mathbf {x}$ Ôüá that minimizes the 2-norm of a vector Ôüá $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {x}$ Ôüá under the constraint $\|\mathbf {x} \|=1.$ The solution turns out to be the right-singular vector of Ôüá $\mathbf {A}$ Ôüá corresponding to the smallest singular value.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] As a consequence, the rank of Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá equals the number of non-zero singular values which is the same as the number of non-zero diagonal elements in $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In numerical linear algebra the singular values can be used to determine the *effective rank* of a matrix, as rounding error may lead to small but non-zero singular values in a rank deficient matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Singular values beyond a significant gap are assumed to be numerically equivalent to zero.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Some practical applications need to solve the problem of approximating a matrix Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá with another matrix ${\tilde {\mathbf {M} }}$ , said to be truncated, which has a specific rank Ôüá r Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This is known as the **EckartÔÇôYoung theorem**, as it was proved by those two authors in 1936.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] One practical consequence of the low-rank approximation given by SVD is that a greyscale image represented as an $m\times n$ matrix $\mathbf {A}$ , can be efficiently represented by keeping the first k singular values and corresponding vectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] $\mathbf {A} _{k}=\sum _{j=1}^{k}\sigma _{j}\mathbf {u} _{j}\mathbf {v} _{j}^{T}$ gives an image with the best 2-norm error out of all rank k approximations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Thus, the task becomes finding an approximation that balances retaining perceptual fidelity with the number of vectors required to reconstruct the image.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Storing $\mathbf {A} _{k}$ requires only $k(n+m+1)$ floating-point numbers compared to $nm$ integers.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This same idea extends to color images by applying this operation to each channel or stacking the channels into one matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Since the singular values of most natural images decay quickly, most of their variance is often captured by a small k .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] For a 1528 ├Ś 1225 greyscale image, we can achieve a relative error of $.7\%$ with as little as $k=100$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In practice, however, computing the SVD can be too computationally expensive and the resulting compression is typically less storage efficient than a specialized algorithm such as JPEG.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD can be thought of as decomposing a matrix into a weighted, ordered sum of separable matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Here Ôüá $\mathbf {U} _{i}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {V} _{i}$ Ôüá are the Ôüá i Ôüá-th columns of the corresponding SVD matrices, Ôüá $\sigma _{i}$ Ôüá are the ordered singular values, and each Ôüá $\mathbf {A} _{i}$ Ôüá is separable.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD can be used to find the decomposition of an image processing filter into separable horizontal and vertical filters.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Note that the number of non-zero Ôüá $\sigma _{i}$ Ôüá is exactly the rank of the matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Separable models often arise in biological systems, and the SVD factorization is useful to analyze such systems.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] For example, some visual area V1 simple cells' receptive fields can be well described by a Gabor filter in the space domain multiplied by a modulation function in the time domain.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Thus, given a linear filter evaluated through, for example, reverse correlation, one can rearrange the two spatial dimensions into one dimension, thus yielding a two-dimensional filter (space, time) which can be decomposed through SVD.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The first column of Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá in the SVD factorization is then a Gabor while the first column of Ôüá $\mathbf {V}$ Ôüá represents the time modulation (or vice versa).
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] which is the fraction of the power in the matrix M which is accounted for by the first separable matrix in the decomposition.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Equivalently, the solution is the unitary matrix Ôüá $\mathbf {R} =\mathbf {U} \mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá of the Polar Decomposition $\mathbf {M} =\mathbf {R} \mathbf {P} =\mathbf {P} '\mathbf {R}$ in either order of stretch and rotation, as described above.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This problem is equivalent to finding the nearest orthogonal matrix to a given matrix $\mathbf {M} =\mathbf {A} ^{\operatorname {T} }\mathbf {B}$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The Kabsch algorithm (called Wahba's problem in other fields) uses SVD to compute the optimal rotation (with respect to least-squares minimization) that will align a set of points with a corresponding set of points.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It is used, among other applications, to compare the structures of molecules.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Let $\mathbf {X} \in \mathbb {R} ^{N\times p}$ be a data matrix where each of the N rows is a (feature-wise) mean-centered observation, each of dimension p .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] We see that $\mathbf {V} {\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}$ contains the scores of the rows of $\mathbf {X}$ (i.e. each observation), and $\mathbf {U}$ is the matrix whose columns are principal component loading vectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD and pseudoinverse have been successfully applied to signal processing, image processing and big data (e.g., in genomic signal processing).
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD is also applied extensively to the study of linear inverse problems and is useful in the analysis of regularization methods such as that of Tikhonov.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It is widely used in statistics, where it is related to principal component analysis and to correspondence analysis, and in signal processing and pattern recognition.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It is also used in output-only modal analysis, where the non-scaled mode shapes can be determined from the singular vectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Yet another usage is latent semantic indexing in natural-language text processing.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In general numerical computation involving linear or linearized systems, there is a universal constant that characterizes the regularity or singularity of a problem, which is the system's "condition number" $\kappa :=\sigma _{\text{max}}/\sigma _{\text{min}}$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It often controls the error rate or convergence rate of a given computational scheme on such systems.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD also plays a crucial role in the field of quantum information, in a form often referred to as the Schmidt decomposition.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Through it, states of two quantum systems are naturally decomposed, providing a necessary and sufficient condition for them to be entangled: if the rank of the $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ matrix is larger than one.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The output singular vectors in this case are entire weather systems.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] These perturbations are then run through the full nonlinear model to generate an ensemble forecast, giving a handle on some of the uncertainty that should be allowed for around the current central prediction.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] SVD has also been applied to reduced order modelling.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The aim of reduced order modelling is to reduce the number of degrees of freedom in a complex system which is to be modeled.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] SVD was coupled with radial basis functions to interpolate solutions to three-dimensional unsteady flow problems.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Interestingly, SVD has been used to improve gravitational waveform modeling by the ground-based gravitational-wave interferometer aLIGO.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] SVD can help to increase the accuracy and speed of waveform generation to support gravitational-waves searches and update two different waveform models.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Singular value decomposition is used in recommender systems to predict people's item ratings.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Distributed algorithms have been developed for the purpose of calculating the SVD on clusters of commodity machines.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Low-rank SVD has been applied for hotspot detection from spatiotemporal data with application to disease outbreak detection.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A combination of SVD and higher-order SVD also has been applied for real time event detection from complex data streams (multivariate data with space and time dimensions) in disease surveillance.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In astrodynamics, the SVD and its variants are used as an option to determine suitable maneuver directions for transfer trajectory design and orbital station-keeping.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD can be used to measure the similarity between real-valued matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] By measuring the angles between the singular vectors, the inherent two-dimensional structure of matrices is accounted for.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This method was shown to outperform cosine similarity and Frobenius norm in most cases, including brain activity measurements from neuroscience experiments.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] An eigenvalue Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá of a matrix Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá is characterized by the algebraic relation Ôüá $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {u} =\lambda \mathbf {u} .$ Ôüá When Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá is Hermitian, a variational characterization is also available.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Let Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá be a real Ôüá $n\times n$ Ôüá symmetric matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The complex Hermitian case is similar; there Ôüá $f(\mathbf {x} )=\mathbf {x} ^{*}\mathbf {M} \mathbf {x}$ Ôüá is a real-valued function of Ôüá $2n$ Ôüá real variables.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Singular values are similar in that they can be described algebraically or from variational principles.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Although, unlike the eigenvalue case, Hermiticity, or symmetry, of Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá is no longer required.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This section gives these two arguments for existence of singular value decomposition.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Let $\mathbf {M}$ be an Ôüá $m\times n$ Ôüá complex matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Note that $\mathbf {V}$ is here by definition a matrix whose i -th column is the i -th eigenvector of $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ , corresponding to the eigenvalue ${\bar {\mathbf {D} }}_{ii}$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Moreover, the j -th column of $\mathbf {V}$ , for $j>\ell$ , is an eigenvector of $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ with eigenvalue ${\bar {\mathbf {D} }}_{jj}=0$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Moreover, the second equation implies $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {V} _{2}=\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] since $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {V} _{2}=\mathbf {0} .$ This can be also seen as immediate consequence of the fact that $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {V} _{1}\mathbf {V} _{1}^{*}=\mathbf {M}$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] We see that this is almost the desired result, except that $\mathbf {U} _{1}$ and $\mathbf {V} _{1}$ are in general not unitary, since they might not be square.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] However, we do know that the number of rows of $\mathbf {U} _{1}$ is no smaller than the number of columns, since the dimensions of $\mathbf {D}$ is no greater than m and n .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This means that we can choose $\mathbf {U} _{2}$ such that $\mathbf {U} ={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {U} _{1}&\mathbf {U} _{2}\end{bmatrix}}$ is unitary.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] For Ôüá $\mathbf {V} _{1}$ Ôüá we already have Ôüá $\mathbf {V} _{2}$ Ôüá to make it unitary.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] where extra zero rows are added **or removed** to make the number of zero rows equal the number of columns of Ôüá $\mathbf {U} _{2},$ Ôüá and hence the overall dimensions of $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ equal to $m\times n$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Notice the argument could begin with diagonalizing Ôüá $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {M} ^{*}$ Ôüá rather than Ôüá $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá (This shows directly that Ôüá $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {M} ^{*}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá have the same non-zero eigenvalues).
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular values can also be characterized as the maxima of Ôüá $\mathbf {u} ^{\mathrm {T} }\mathbf {M} \mathbf {v} ,$ Ôüá considered as a function of Ôüá $\mathbf {u}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {v} ,$ Ôüá over particular subspaces.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular vectors are the values of Ôüá $\mathbf {u}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {v}$ Ôüá where these maxima are attained.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Let Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá denote an Ôüá $m\times n$ Ôüá matrix with real entries.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Consider the function Ôüá $\sigma$ Ôüá restricted to Ôüá $S^{m-1}\times S^{n-1}.$ Ôüá Since both Ôüá $S^{m-1}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $S^{n-1}$ Ôüá are compact sets, their product is also compact.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If it were negative, changing the sign of either Ôüá $\mathbf {u} _{1}$ Ôüá or Ôüá $\mathbf {v} _{1}$ Ôüá would make it positive and therefore larger.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] More singular vectors and singular values can be found by maximizing Ôüá $\sigma (\mathbf {u} ,\mathbf {v} )$ Ôüá over normalized Ôüá $\mathbf {u}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {v}$ Ôüá which are orthogonal to Ôüá $\mathbf {u} _{1}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {v} _{1},$ Ôüá respectively.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The passage from real to complex is similar to the eigenvalue case.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] One-sided Jacobi algorithm is an iterative algorithm, where a matrix is iteratively transformed into a matrix with orthogonal columns.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The elementary iteration is given as a Jacobi rotation, $M\leftarrow MJ(p,q,\theta ),$ where the angle $\theta$ of the Jacobi rotation matrix $J(p,q,\theta )$ is chosen such that after the rotation the columns with numbers p and q become orthogonal.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The indices $(p,q)$ are swept cyclically, $(p=1\dots m,q=p+1\dots m)$ , where m is the number of columns.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Two-sided Jacobi SVD algorithmÔÇöa generalization of the Jacobi eigenvalue algorithmÔÇöis an iterative algorithm where a square matrix is iteratively transformed into a diagonal matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If the matrix is not square the QR decomposition is performed first and then the algorithm is applied to the R matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The iterations proceeds exactly as in the Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm: by cyclic sweeps over all off-diagonal elements.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] After the algorithm has converged the resulting diagonal matrix contains the singular values.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The SVD of a matrix Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá is typically computed by a two-step procedure.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In the first step, the matrix is reduced to a bidiagonal matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This takes order Ôüá $O(mn^{2})$ Ôüá floating-point operations (*flop*), assuming that Ôüá $m\geq n.$ Ôüá The second step is to compute the SVD of the bidiagonal matrix.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This step can only be done with an iterative method (as with eigenvalue algorithms).
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] However, in practice it suffices to compute the SVD up to a certain precision, like the machine epsilon.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If this precision is considered constant, then the second step takes Ôüá $O(n)$ Ôüá iterations, each costing Ôüá $O(n)$ Ôüá flops.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Thus, the first step is more expensive, and the overall cost is Ôüá $O(mn^{2})$ Ôüá flops.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The first step can be done using Householder reflections for a cost of Ôüá $4mn^{2}-4n^{3}/3$ Ôüá flops, assuming that only the singular values are needed and not the singular vectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If Ôüá m Ôüá is much larger than Ôüá n Ôüá then it is advantageous to first reduce the matrix Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá to a triangular matrix with the QR decomposition and then use Householder reflections to further reduce the matrix to bidiagonal form; the combined cost is Ôüá $2mn^{2}+2n^{3}$ Ôüá flops.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The second step can be done by a variant of the QR algorithm for the computation of eigenvalues, which was first described by Golub and Kahan in 1965.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The LAPACK subroutine `DBDSQR` implements this iterative method, with some modifications to cover the case where the singular values are very small.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Together with a first step using Householder reflections and, if appropriate, QR decomposition, this forms the `DGESVD` routine for the computation of the singular value decomposition.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The same algorithm is implemented in the GNU Scientific Library (GSL).
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The GSL also offers an alternative method that uses a one-sided Jacobi orthogonalization in step 2.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This method computes the SVD of the bidiagonal matrix by solving a sequence of Ôüá $2\times 2$ Ôüá SVD problems, similar to how the Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm solves a sequence of Ôüá $2\times 2$ Ôüá eigenvalue methods.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Yet another method for step 2 uses the idea of divide-and-conquer eigenvalue algorithms.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] There is an alternative way that does not explicitly use the eigenvalue decomposition.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The approaches that use eigenvalue decompositions are based on the QR algorithm, which is well-developed to be stable and fast.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Note that the singular values are real and right- and left- singular vectors are not required to form similarity transformations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] One can iteratively alternate between the QR decomposition and the LQ decomposition to find the real diagonal Hermitian matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Eventually, this iteration between QR decomposition and LQ decomposition produces left- and right- unitary singular matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This approach cannot readily be accelerated, as the QR algorithm can with spectral shifts or deflation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This is because the shift method is not easily defined without using similarity transformations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] However, this iterative approach is very simple to implement, so is a good choice when speed does not matter.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This method also provides insight into how purely orthogonal/unitary transformations can obtain the SVD.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The methods above yield Ôüá $O(mn^{2})$ Ôüá algorithms for the SVD of an $m\times n$ matrix M where $m\geq n$ .
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Demmel, Dumitriu and Holtz show that for a symmetric M (i.e. $m=n$ ) the SVD can normwise stably be computed in $O(n^{\omega +\eta })$ arithmetic operations where $\omega$ is the matrix multiplication exponent and $\eta >0$ is any constant, i.e. essentially in matrix multiplication time.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular values of a Ôüá $2\times 2$ Ôüá matrix can be found analytically.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] where $z_{i}\in \mathbb {C}$ are complex numbers that parameterize the matrix, Ôüá $\mathbf {I}$ Ôüá is the identity matrix, and $\sigma _{i}$ denote the Pauli matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In applications it is quite unusual for the full SVD, including a full unitary decomposition of the null-space of the matrix, to be required.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Instead, it is often sufficient (as well as faster, and more economical for storage) to compute a reduced version of the SVD.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The thin SVD uses significantly less space and computation time if Ôüá $k\ll \max(m,n).$ Ôüá The first stage in its calculation will usually be a QR decomposition of Ôüá $\mathbf {M} ,$ Ôüá which can make for a significantly quicker calculation in this case.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Only the Ôüá r Ôüá column vectors of Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and Ôüá r Ôüá row vectors of Ôüá $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá corresponding to the non-zero singular values Ôüá $\mathbf {\Sigma } _{r}$ Ôüá are calculated.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The remaining vectors of Ôüá $\mathbf {U}$ Ôüá and Ôüá $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá are not calculated.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In many applications the number Ôüá r Ôüá of the non-zero singular values is large making even the Compact SVD impractical to compute.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In such cases, the smallest singular values may need to be truncated to compute only Ôüá $t\ll r$ Ôüá non-zero singular values.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This can be much quicker and more economical than the compact SVD if Ôüá $t\ll r,$ Ôüá but requires a completely different toolset of numerical solvers.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In applications that require an approximation to the MooreÔÇôPenrose inverse of the matrix Ôüá $\mathbf {M} ,$ Ôüá the smallest singular values of Ôüá $\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá are of interest, which are more challenging to compute compared to the largest ones.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Truncated SVD is employed in latent semantic indexing.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] For this reason, it is also called the operator 2-norm.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] One can easily verify the relationship between the Ky Fan 1-norm and singular values.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The last of the Ky Fan norms, the sum of all singular values, is the trace norm (also known as the 'nuclear norm'), defined by $\|\mathbf {M} \|=\operatorname {Tr} (\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M} )^{1/2}$ (the eigenvalues of Ôüá $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ Ôüá are the squares of the singular values).
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular values are related to another norm on the space of operators.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In addition, the Frobenius norm and the trace norm (the nuclear norm) are special cases of the Schatten norm.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This can be shown by mimicking the linear algebraic argument for the matrix case above. Ôüá $\mathbf {V} T_{f}\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá is the unique positive square root of Ôüá $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M} ,$ Ôüá as given by the Borel functional calculus for self-adjoint operators.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] and notice that Ôüá $\mathbf {U} \mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá is still a partial isometry while Ôüá $\mathbf {V} T_{f}\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ Ôüá is positive.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The notion of singular values and left/right-singular vectors can be extended to compact operator on Hilbert space as they have a discrete spectrum.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If Ôüá T Ôüá is compact, every non-zero Ôüá $\lambda$ Ôüá in its spectrum is an eigenvalue.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Furthermore, a compact self-adjoint operator can be diagonalized by its eigenvectors.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Applying the diagonalization result, the unitary image of its positive square root Ôüá $T_{f}$ Ôüá has a set of orthonormal eigenvectors Ôüá $\{e_{i}\}$ Ôüá corresponding to strictly positive eigenvalues Ôüá $\{\sigma _{i}\}$ Ôüá.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Compact operators on a Hilbert space are the closure of finite-rank operators in the uniform operator topology.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The above series expression gives an explicit such representation.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular value decomposition was originally developed by differential geometers, who wished to determine whether a real bilinear form could be made equal to another by independent orthogonal transformations of the two spaces it acts on.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Eugenio Beltrami and Camille Jordan discovered independently, in 1873 and 1874 respectively, that the singular values of the bilinear forms, represented as a matrix, form a complete set of invariants for bilinear forms under orthogonal substitutions.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] James Joseph Sylvester also arrived at the singular value decomposition for real square matrices in 1889, apparently independently of both Beltrami and Jordan.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Sylvester called the singular values the *canonical multipliers* of the matrix Ôüá $\mathbf {A} .$ Ôüá The fourth mathematician to discover the singular value decomposition independently is Autonne in 1915, who arrived at it via the polar decomposition.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The first proof of the singular value decomposition for rectangular and complex matrices seems to be by Carl Eckart and Gale J.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Young in 1936; they saw it as a generalization of the principal axis transformation for Hermitian matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In 1907, Erhard Schmidt defined an analog of singular values for integral operators (which are compact, under some weak technical assumptions); it seems he was unaware of the parallel work on singular values of finite matrices.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This theory was further developed by ├ëmile Picard in 1910, who is the first to call the numbers $\sigma _{k}$ *singular values* (or in French, *valeurs singuli├Ęres*).
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Practical methods for computing the SVD date back to Kogbetliantz in 1954ÔÇô1955 and Hestenes in 1958, resembling closely the Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm, which uses plane rotations or Givens rotations.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] However, these were replaced by the method of Gene Golub and William Kahan published in 1965, which uses Householder transformations or reflections.
[src:principal-component-analysis/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In 1970, Golub and Christian Reinsch published a variant of the Golub/Kahan algorithm that is still the one most-used today.
